# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cancer-biology
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Angiogenesis is a normal and vital process in growth and development, as well as in wound healing and in the formation of granulation tissue.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] However, it is also a fundamental step in the transition of tumors from a benign to malignant state, leading to the use of angiogenesis inhibitors in the treatment of cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] The essential role of angiogenesis in tumor growth was first proposed in 1971 by Judah Folkman, who described tumors as "hot and bloody," illustrating that, at least for many tumor types, flush perfusion and even hyperemia are characteristic.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Sprouting angiogenesis was the first identified form of angiogenesis and because of this, it is much more understood than intussusceptive angiogenesis.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] It occurs in several well-characterized stages.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] The initial signal comes from tissue areas that are devoid of vasculature.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] The hypoxia that is noted in these areas causes the tissues to demand the presence of nutrients and oxygen that will allow the tissue to carry out metabolic activities.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Because of this, parenchymal cells will secrete vascular endothelial growth factor (VEGF-A) which is a proangiogenic growth factor.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] These biological signals activate receptors on endothelial cells present in pre-existing blood vessels.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Second, the activated endothelial cells, also known as **tip cells**, begin to release enzymes called proteases that degrade the basement membrane to allow endothelial cells to escape from the original (parent) vessel walls.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] The endothelial cells then proliferate into the surrounding matrix and form solid sprouts connecting neighboring vessels.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] The cells that are proliferating are located behind the tip cells and are known as **stalk cells**.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] The proliferation of these cells allows the capillary sprout to grow in length simultaneously.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] As sprouts extend toward the source of the angiogenic stimulus, endothelial cells migrate in tandem, using adhesion molecules called integrins.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] These sprouts then form loops to become a full-fledged vessel lumen as cells migrate to the site of angiogenesis.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Sprouting occurs at a rate of several millimeters per day, and enables new vessels to grow across gaps in the vasculature.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] It is markedly different from splitting angiogenesis because it forms entirely new vessels as opposed to splitting existing vessels.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Intussusceptive angiogenesis, also known as *splitting angiogenesis*, is the formation of a new blood vessel by splitting an existing blood vessel into two.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Intussusception was first observed in neonatal rats.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] In this type of vessel formation, the capillary wall extends into the lumen to split a single vessel in two.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] There are four phases of intussusceptive angiogenesis.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] First, the two opposing capillary walls establish a zone of contact.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Second, the endothelial cell junctions are reorganized and the vessel bilayer is perforated to allow growth factors and cells to penetrate into the lumen.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Third, a core is formed between the 2 new vessels at the zone of contact that is filled with pericytes and myofibroblasts.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] These cells begin laying collagen fibers into the core to provide an extracellular matrix for growth of the vessel lumen.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Finally, the core is fleshed out with no alterations to the basic structure.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Intussusception is important because it is a reorganization of existing cells.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] It allows a vast increase in the number of capillaries without a corresponding increase in the number of endothelial cells.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] This is especially important in embryonic development as there are not enough resources to create a rich microvasculature with new cells every time a new vessel develops.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Coalescent angiogenesis is a mode of angiogenesis, considered to be the opposite of intussusceptive angiogenesis, where capillaries fuse, or coalesce, to make a larger bloodvessel, thereby increasing blood flow and circulation.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Coalescent angiogenesis has extended out of the domain of embryology.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] It is assumed to play a role in the formation of neovasculature, such as in a tumor.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Mechanical stimulation of angiogenesis is not well characterized.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] There is a significant amount of controversy with regard to shear stress acting on capillaries to cause angiogenesis, although current knowledge suggests that increased muscle contractions may increase angiogenesis.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] This may be due to an increase in the production of nitric oxide during exercise.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Nitric oxide results in vasodilation of blood vessels.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Beyond fluid shear stress, the water channel AQP1 contributes to the mechanical expansion of the cell membrane during migration.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] By facilitating localized water influx at the leading edge, AQP1 creates the hydrostatic pressure necessary to drive membrane protrusions, which is a critical physical step in the formation of new vascular sprouts.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Chemical stimulation of angiogenesis is performed by various angiogenic proteins e.g. integrins and prostaglandins, including several growth factors e.g.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] The fibroblast growth factor (FGF) family with its prototype members FGF-1 (acidic FGF) and FGF-2 (basic FGF) consists to date of at least 22 known members.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Most are single-chain peptides of 16-18 kDa and display high affinity to heparin and heparan sulfate.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] In general, FGFs stimulate a variety of cellular functions by binding to cell surface FGF-receptors in the presence of heparin proteoglycans.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] The FGF-receptor family is composed of seven members, and all the receptor proteins are single-chain receptor tyrosine kinases that become activated through autophosphorylation induced by a mechanism of FGF-mediated receptor dimerization.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Besides FGF-1, one of the most important functions of fibroblast growth factor-2 (FGF-2 or bFGF) is the promotion of endothelial cell proliferation and the physical organization of endothelial cells into tube-like structures, thus promoting angiogenesis.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] FGF-2 is a more potent angiogenic factor than VEGF or PDGF (platelet-derived growth factor); however, it is less potent than FGF-1.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] As well as stimulating blood vessel growth, aFGF (FGF-1) and bFGF (FGF-2) are important players in wound healing.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] They stimulate the proliferation of fibroblasts and endothelial cells that give rise to angiogenesis and developing granulation tissue; both increase blood supply and fill up a wound space/cavity early in the wound-healing process.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Vascular endothelial growth factor (VEGF) has been demonstrated to be a major contributor to angiogenesis, increasing the number of capillaries in a given network.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Initial *in vitro* studies demonstrated bovine capillary endothelial cells will proliferate and show signs of tube structures upon stimulation by VEGF and bFGF, although the results were more pronounced with VEGF.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Upregulation of VEGF is a major component of the physiological response to exercise and its role in angiogenesis is suspected to be a possible treatment in vascular injuries.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] *In vitro* studies clearly demonstrate that VEGF is a potent stimulator of angiogenesis because, in the presence of this growth factor, plated endothelial cells will proliferate and migrate, eventually forming tube structures resembling capillaries.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] VEGF causes a massive signaling cascade in endothelial cells.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Mechanically, VEGF is upregulated with muscle contractions as a result of increased blood flow to affected areas.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] The increased flow also causes a large increase in the mRNA production of VEGF receptors 1 and 2.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] The increase in receptor production means muscle contractions could cause upregulation of the signaling cascade relating to angiogenesis.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] As part of the angiogenic signaling cascade, NO is widely considered to be a major contributor to the angiogenic response because inhibition of NO significantly reduces the effects of angiogenic growth factors.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] However, inhibition of NO during exercise does not inhibit angiogenesis, indicating there are other factors involved in the angiogenic response.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] The angiopoietins, Ang1 and Ang2, are required for the formation of mature blood vessels, as demonstrated by mouse knock out studies.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Ang1 and Ang2 are protein growth factors which act by binding their receptors, Tie-1 and Tie-2; while this is somewhat controversial, it seems that cell signals are transmitted mostly by Tie-2; though some papers show physiologic signaling via Tie-1 as well.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Thus, they can initiate cell signaling when ligand binding causes a dimerization that initiates phosphorylation on key tyrosines.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Another major contributor to angiogenesis is matrix metalloproteinase (MMP).
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] MMPs help degrade the proteins that keep the vessel walls solid.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] This proteolysis allows the endothelial cells to escape into the interstitial matrix as seen in sprouting angiogenesis.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Inhibition of MMPs prevents the formation of new capillaries.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] These enzymes are highly regulated during the vessel formation process because destruction of the extracellular matrix would decrease the integrity of the microvasculature.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Delta-like ligand 4 (Dll4) is a protein with a negative regulatory effect on angiogenesis.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Dll4 is a transmembrane ligand, for the notch family of receptors.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] There have been many studies conducted that have served to determine consequences of the Delta-like Ligand 4.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] One study in particular evaluated the effects of Dll4 on tumor vascularity and growth.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] In order for a tumor to grow and develop, it must have the proper vasculature.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] The VEGF pathway is vital to the development of vasculature that in turn, helps the tumors to grow.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] The combined blockade of VEGF and Dll4 results in the inhibition of tumor progression and angiogenesis throughout the tumor.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] This is due to the hindrance of signaling in endothelial cell signaling which cuts off the proliferation and sprouting of these endothelial cells.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] With this inhibition, the cells do not uncontrollably grow, therefore, the cancer is stopped at this point. if the blockade, however, were to be lifted, the cells would begin their proliferation once again.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Class 3 semaphorins (SEMA3s) regulate angiogenesis by modulating endothelial cell adhesion, migration, proliferation, survival and the recruitment of pericytes.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Furthermore, semaphorins can interfere with VEGF-mediated angiogenesis since both SEMA3s and VEGF-A compete for neuropilin receptor binding at endothelial cells.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] The relative expression levels of SEMA3s and VEGF-A may therefore be important for angiogenesis.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] An angiogenesis inhibitor can be endogenous or come from outside as drug or a dietary component.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Angiogenesis may be a target for combating diseases such as heart disease characterized by either poor vascularisation or abnormal vasculature.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Application of specific compounds that may inhibit or induce the creation of new blood vessels in the body may help combat such diseases.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] The presence of blood vessels where there should be none may affect the mechanical properties of a tissue, increasing the likelihood of failure.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] The absence of blood vessels in a repairing or otherwise metabolically active tissue may inhibit repair or other essential functions.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Several diseases, such as ischemic chronic wounds, are the result of failure or insufficient blood vessel formation and may be treated by a local expansion of blood vessels, thus bringing new nutrients to the site, facilitating repair.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Other diseases, such as age-related macular degeneration, may be created by a local expansion of blood vessels, interfering with normal physiological processes.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] The modern clinical application of the principle of angiogenesis can be divided into two main areas: anti-angiogenic therapies, which angiogenic research began with, and pro-angiogenic therapies.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Whereas anti-angiogenic therapies are being employed to fight cancer and malignancies, which require an abundance of oxygen and nutrients to proliferate, pro-angiogenic therapies are being explored as options to treat cardiovascular diseases, the number one cause of death in the Western world.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] One of the first applications of pro-angiogenic methods in humans was a German trial using fibroblast growth factor 1 (FGF-1) for the treatment of coronary artery disease.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] There are still serious, unsolved problems related to gene therapy.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] The most commonly occurring disorders in humans, such as heart disease, high blood pressure, diabetes and Alzheimer's disease, are most likely caused by the combined effects of variations in many genes, and, thus, injecting a single gene may not be significantly beneficial in such diseases.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] By contrast, pro-angiogenic protein therapy uses well-defined, precisely structured proteins, with previously defined optimal doses of the individual protein for disease states, and with well-known biological effects.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] On the other hand, an obstacle of protein therapy is the mode of delivery.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Oral, intravenous, intra-arterial, or intramuscular routes of protein administration are not always as effective, as the therapeutic protein may be metabolized or cleared before it can enter the target tissue.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Cell-based pro-angiogenic therapies are still early stages of research, with many open questions regarding best cell types and dosages to use.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Cancer cells are cells that have lost their ability to divide in a controlled fashion.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] A malignant tumor consists of a population of rapidly dividing and growing cancer cells that progressively accrues mutations.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] However, tumors need a dedicated blood supply to provide the oxygen and other essential nutrients they require in order to grow beyond a certain size (generally 1–2 mm3).
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Tumors induce blood vessel growth (angiogenesis) by secreting various growth factors (e.g.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Growth factors such as bFGF and VEGF can induce capillary growth into the tumor, which some researchers suspect supply required nutrients, allowing for tumor expansion.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Unlike normal blood vessels, tumor blood vessels are dilated with an irregular shape.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Other clinicians believe angiogenesis really serves as a waste pathway, taking away the biological end products secreted by rapidly dividing cancer cells.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] In either case, angiogenesis is a necessary and required step for transition from a small harmless cluster of cells, often said to be about the size of the metal ball at the end of a ball-point pen, to a large tumor.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Angiogenesis is also required for the spread of a tumor, or metastasis.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Single cancer cells can break away from an established solid tumor, enter the blood vessel, and be carried to a distant site, where they can implant and begin the growth of a secondary tumor.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Evidence now suggests the blood vessel in a given solid tumor may, in fact, be mosaic vessels, composed of endothelial cells and tumor cells.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] This mosaicity allows for substantial shedding of tumor cells into the vasculature, possibly contributing to the appearance of circulating tumor cells in the peripheral blood of patients with malignancies.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] The subsequent growth of such metastases will also require a supply of nutrients and oxygen and a waste disposal pathway.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Endothelial cells have long been considered genetically more stable than cancer cells.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] This genomic stability confers an advantage to targeting endothelial cells using anti-angiogenic therapy, compared to chemotherapy directed at cancer cells, which rapidly mutate and acquire drug resistance to treatment.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Thus, endothelial cells are thought to be an ideal target for therapies against cancer..
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Currently, there have been multiple clinical trials using anti-angiogenic therapies in combination with other therapeutic agents (e.g chemotherapy for treatment of various cancers.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] The mechanism of blood vessel formation by angiogenesis is initiated by the spontaneous dividing of tumor cells due to a mutation.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Angiogenic stimulators are then released by the tumor cells.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] These then travel to already established, nearby blood vessels and activates their endothelial cell receptors.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] This induces a release of proteolytic enzymes from the vasculature.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] These enzymes target a particular point on the blood vessel and cause a pore to form.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] This is the point where the new blood vessel will grow from.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] The reason tumour cells need a blood supply is because they cannot grow any more than 2-3 millimeters in diameter without an established blood supply which is equivalent to about 50-100 cells.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Certain studies have indicated that vessels formed inside the tumor tissue are of higher irregularity and bigger in size, which is as well associated with poorer prognosis.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Angiogenesis represents an excellent therapeutic target for the treatment of cardiovascular disease.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] It is a potent, physiological process that underlies the natural manner in which our bodies respond to a diminution of blood supply to vital organs, namely *neoangiogenesis*: the production of new collateral vessels to overcome the ischemic insult.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] A large number of preclinical studies have been performed with protein-, gene- and cell-based therapies in animal models of cardiac ischemia, as well as models of peripheral artery disease.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Reproducible and credible successes in these early animal studies led to high enthusiasm that this new therapeutic approach could be rapidly translated to a clinical benefit for millions of patients in the Western world with these disorders.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] A decade of clinical testing both gene- and protein-based therapies designed to stimulate angiogenesis in underperfused tissues and organs, however, has led from one disappointment to another.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] It may be necessary to present these proteins in a way that mimics natural signaling events, including the concentration, spatial and temporal profiles, and their simultaneous or sequential presentation with other appropriate factors.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Early experimental evidence that skeletal muscle contraction induces vascular endothelial growth factor (VEGF) expression came from studies using electrically stimulated muscle.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] (1995) demonstrated that electrically stimulated skeletal muscle exhibited significant upregulation of VEGF expression, establishing skeletal muscle fibers as an active source of angiogenic signaling.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] This work preceded later exercise-training studies and contributed to the understanding of VEGF as a contraction-responsive factor involved in skeletal muscle angiogenesis.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Angiogenesis is generally associated with aerobic exercise and endurance exercise.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] While arteriogenesis produces network changes that enable a large increase in total flow, angiogenesis produces changes that enable greater nutrient delivery over a longer period.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Capillaries are designed to provide maximum nutrient delivery efficiency, so an increase in the number of capillaries allows the network to deliver more nutrients in the same amount of time.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] A greater number of capillaries also allows for greater oxygen exchange in the network.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] This is vitally important to endurance training, because it allows a person to continue training for an extended period of time.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] However, no experimental evidence suggests that increased capillarity is required in endurance exercise to increase the maximum oxygen delivery.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Overexpression of VEGF causes increased permeability in blood vessels in addition to stimulating angiogenesis.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] In wet macular degeneration, VEGF causes proliferation of capillaries into the retina.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Since the increase in angiogenesis also causes edema, blood and other retinal fluids leak into the retina, causing loss of vision.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Angiogenesis of vessels from the host body into an implanted tissue engineered constructs is essential.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Successful integration is often dependent on thorough vascularisation of the construct as it provides oxygen and nutrients and prevents necrosis in the central areas of the implant.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] PDGF has been shown to stabilize vascularisation in collagen-glycosaminoglycan scaffolds.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] The first report of angiogenesis can be traced back to the book *A treatise on the blood, inflammation, and gun-shot wounds* published in 1794, where Scottish anatomist John Hunter's research findings were compiled.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] In his study, Hunter observed the growth process of new blood vessels in rabbits.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] However, he did not coin the term "Angiogenesis," which is now widely used by scholars.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Hunter also erroneously attributed the growth process of new blood vessels to the effect of an innate vital principle within the blood.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] The term "angiogenesis" is believed to have emerged not until the 1900s.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] The inception of modern angiogenesis research is marked by Judah Folkman's report on the pivotal role of angiogenesis in tumor growth.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Quantifying vasculature parameters such as microvascular density has various complications due to preferential staining or limited representation of tissues by histological sections.
[src:cancer-biology/angiogenesis] Recent research has shown complete 3D reconstruction of tumor vascular structure and quantification of vessel structures in whole tumors in animal models.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] About 33% of deaths from cancer are caused by tobacco and alcohol, obesity, lack of fruit and vegetables in the diet and lack of exercise.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Other factors include certain infections, exposure to ionizing radiation, and environmental pollutants.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Infection with specific viruses, bacteria, and parasites causes approximately 16–18% of cancers worldwide.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] These infectious agents include *Helicobacter pylori*, hepatitis B, hepatitis C, and HPV.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) does not directly cause cancer, but it causes immune deficiency that can increase the risk of cancer from other infections, sometimes up to several thousandfold.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Vaccination against the hepatitis B virus and the human papillomavirus have been shown to nearly eliminate the risk of cancers caused by these viruses.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] These environmental factors act, at least partly, by changing the genes of a cell.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Typically, many genetic changes are required before cancer develops.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Approximately 5–10% of cancers are due to inherited genetic defects.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Cancer can be detected by certain signs and symptoms or screening tests.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] It is then typically further investigated by medical imaging and confirmed by biopsy.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Early detection through screening is useful for cervical and colorectal cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] The benefits of screening for breast cancer are controversial.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Cancer is often treated with some combination of radiation therapy, surgery, chemotherapy and targeted therapy.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] More personalized therapies that harness a patient's immune system are emerging in the field of cancer immunotherapy.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Palliative care is a medical specialty that delivers advanced pain and symptom management, which may be particularly important in those with advanced disease.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] The chance of survival depends on the type of cancer and extent of disease at the start of treatment.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] In children under 15 at diagnosis, the five-year survival rate in the developed world is on average 80%.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] For cancer in the United States, the average five-year survival rate is 66% for all ages.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] In 2015, about 90.5 million people worldwide had cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] In 2019, annual cancer cases grew by 23.6 million people, and there were 10 million deaths worldwide, representing over the previous decade increases of 26% and 21%, respectively.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] The most common types of cancer in males are lung cancer, prostate cancer, colorectal cancer, and stomach cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] In females, the most common types are breast cancer, colorectal cancer, lung cancer, and cervical cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] If skin cancer other than melanoma were included in total new cancer cases each year, it would account for around 40% of cases.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] In children, acute lymphoblastic leukemia and brain tumors are most common, except in Africa, where non-Hodgkin lymphoma occurs more often.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] In 2012, about 165,000 children under 15 years of age were diagnosed with cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] The risk of cancer increases significantly with age, and many cancers occur more commonly in developed countries.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Rates are increasing as more people live to an old age and as lifestyle changes occur in the developing world.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] The global total economic costs of cancer were estimated at US$1.16 trillion (equivalent to $1.71 trillion in 2025) per year as of 2010.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] The word comes from the ancient Greek καρκίνος, meaning 'crab' and 'tumor'.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Greek physicians Hippocrates and Galen, among others, noted the similarity of crabs to some tumors with swollen veins.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] The word was introduced in English in the modern medical sense around 1600.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Cancers comprise a large family of diseases that involve abnormal cell growth with the potential to invade or spread to other parts of the body.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] A neoplasm or tumor is a group of cells that have undergone unregulated growth and will often form a mass or lump, but may be distributed diffusely.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] All tumor cells show the six hallmarks of cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] These characteristics are required to produce a malignant tumor.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] The progression from normal cells to cells that can form a detectable mass to cancer involves multiple steps known as malignant progression.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] When cancer begins, it produces no symptoms.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Signs and symptoms appear as the mass grows or ulcerates.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] The findings that result depend on cancer's type and location.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Many frequently occur in individuals who have other conditions.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Cancer can be difficult to diagnose and can be considered a "great imitator".
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] People may become anxious or depressed post-diagnosis.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] The risk of suicide in people with cancer is approximately double.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Local symptoms may occur due to the mass of the tumor or its ulceration.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] For example, mass effects from lung cancer can block the bronchus resulting in cough or pneumonia; esophageal cancer can cause narrowing of the esophagus, making it difficult or painful to swallow; and colorectal cancer may lead to narrowing or blockages in the bowel, affecting bowel habits.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Masses in breasts or testicles may produce observable lumps.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Ulceration can cause bleeding that can lead to symptoms such as coughing up blood (lung cancer), anemia or rectal bleeding (colon cancer), blood in the urine (bladder cancer), or abnormal vaginal bleeding (endometrial or cervical cancer).
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Although localized pain may occur in advanced cancer, the initial tumor is usually painless.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Some cancers can cause a buildup of fluid within the chest or abdomen.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Systemic symptoms may occur due to the body's response to the cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] This may include fatigue, unintentional weight loss, or skin changes.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Some cancers can cause a systemic inflammatory state that leads to ongoing muscle loss and weakness, known as cachexia.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Some cancers, such as Hodgkin's disease, leukemias, and liver or kidney cancers, can cause a persistent fever.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Shortness of breath, called dyspnea, is a common symptom of cancer and its treatment.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] The causes of cancer-related dyspnea can include tumors in or around the lung, blocked airways, fluid in the lungs, pneumonia, or treatment reactions including an allergic response.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Treatment for dyspnea in patients with advanced cancer can include fans, bilevel ventilation, acupressure/reflexology and multicomponent nonpharmacological interventions.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Some systemic symptoms of cancer are caused by hormones or other molecules produced by the tumor, known as paraneoplastic syndromes.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Common paraneoplastic syndromes include hypercalcemia, which can cause altered mental state, constipation and dehydration, or hyponatremia, which can also cause altered mental status, vomiting, headaches, or seizures.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Metastasis is the spread of cancer to other locations in the body.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] The dispersed tumors are called metastatic tumors, while the original is called the primary tumor.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Most cancer deaths are due to cancer that has metastasized.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Metastasis is common in the late stages of cancer and it can occur via the blood or the lymphatic system or both.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Different types of cancers tend to metastasize to particular organs.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Overall, the most common places for metastases to occur are the lungs, liver, brain, and the bones.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] While some cancers can be cured if detected early, metastatic cancer is more difficult to treat and control.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Nevertheless, some recent treatments are demonstrating encouraging results.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] The majority of cancers, some 90–95% of cases, are due to environmental and lifestyle factors.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] The remaining 5–10% are due to inherited genetics.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] *Environmental* refers to any cause that is not inherited, such as lifestyle, economic, and behavioral factors and not merely pollution.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Common environmental factors that contribute to cancer death include tobacco use (25–30%), diet and obesity (30–35%), infections (15–20%), radiation (both ionizing and non-ionizing, up to 10%), lack of physical activity, and pollution.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Psychological stress does not appear to be a risk factor for the onset of cancer, though it may worsen outcomes in those who already have cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Environmental or lifestyle factors that caused cancer to develop in an individual can be identified by analyzing mutational signatures from genomic sequencing of tumor DNA.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] For example, this can reveal if lung cancer was caused by tobacco smoke, if skin cancer was caused by UV radiation, or if secondary cancers were caused by previous chemotherapy treatment.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Cancer is generally not a transmissible disease.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Exceptions include rare transmissions that occur with pregnancies and occasional organ donors.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] However, transmissible infectious diseases such as hepatitis B, Epstein–Barr, HPV and HIV infections, can contribute to the development of cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Exposure to particular substances has been linked to specific types of cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] These substances are called *carcinogens*.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Tobacco smoke, for example, causes 90% of lung cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Tobacco use can cause cancer throughout the body including in the mouth and throat, larynx, esophagus, stomach, bladder, kidney, cervix, colon/rectum, liver and pancreas.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Tobacco smoke contains over fifty known carcinogens, including nitrosamines and polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Tobacco is responsible for about one in five cancer deaths worldwide and about one in three in the developed world.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Lung cancer death rates in the United States have mirrored smoking patterns, with increases in smoking followed by dramatic increases in lung cancer death rates and, more recently, decreases in smoking rates since the 1950s followed by decreases in lung cancer death rates in men since 1990.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Alcohol increases the risk of cancer of the breast (in women), throat, liver, osophagus, mouth, larynx, and colon.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] In Western Europe, 10% of cancers in males and 3% of cancers in females are attributed to alcohol, especially liver and digestive tract cancers.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Cancer from work-related substance exposures may cause between 2 and 20% of cases, causing at least 200,000 deaths.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Cancers such as lung cancer and mesothelioma can come from inhaling tobacco smoke or asbestos fibers, or leukemia from exposure to benzene.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Exposure to perfluorooctanoic acid (PFOA), which is predominantly used in the production of Teflon, has been associated with an increased risk of kidney cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Chemotherapy drugs such as platinum-based compounds are carcinogens that increase the risk of secondary cancers.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Azathioprine, an immunosuppressive medication, is a carcinogen that can cause primary tumors to develop.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Diet, physical inactivity, and obesity are related to up to 30–35% of cancer deaths.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] In the United States, excess body weight is associated with the development of many types of cancer and is a factor in 14–20% of cancer deaths.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] A UK study including data on over 5 million people showed higher body mass index to be related to at least 10 types of cancer and responsible for around 12,000 cases each year in that country.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Physical inactivity is believed to contribute to cancer risk, not only through its effect on body weight but also through negative effects on the immune system and endocrine system.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] More than half of the effect from the diet is due to overnutrition (eating too much), rather than from eating too few vegetables or other healthful foods.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Some specific foods are linked to specific cancers.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] A high-salt diet is linked to gastric cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Aflatoxin B1, a frequent food contaminant, causes liver cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Betel nut chewing can cause oral cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] National differences in dietary practices may partly explain differences in cancer incidence.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] For example, gastric cancer is more common in Japan due to its high-salt diet while colon cancer is more common in the United States.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Immigrant cancer profiles mirror those of their new country, often within one generation.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Worldwide, approximately 18% of cancer deaths are related to infectious diseases.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] This proportion ranges from a high of 25% in Africa to less than 10% in the developed world.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Viruses are the usual infectious agents that cause cancer but bacteria and parasites may also play a role.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Radiation exposure such as ultraviolet radiation and radioactive material is a risk factor for cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Many non-melanoma skin cancers are due to ultraviolet radiation, mostly from sunlight.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Sources of ionizing radiation include medical imaging and radon gas.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Residential exposure to radon gas has similar cancer risks as passive smoking.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Radiation is a more potent source of cancer when combined with other cancer-causing agents, such as radon plus tobacco smoke.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Radiation can cause cancer in most parts of the body, and at any age.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Children are twice as likely to develop radiation-induced leukemia as adults; radiation exposure before birth has ten times the effect.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Medical use of ionizing radiation is a small but growing source of radiation-induced cancers.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Ionizing radiation may be used to treat other cancers, but this may, in some cases, induce a second form of cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] It is also used in some kinds of medical imaging.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Prolonged exposure to ultraviolet radiation from the sun can lead to melanoma and other skin malignancies.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Ultraviolet radiation, especially the non-ionizing medium wave UVB, is the cause of most non-melanoma skin cancers, which are the most common forms of cancer in the world.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Non-ionizing radio frequency radiation from mobile phones, electric power transmission and other similar sources has been described as a possible carcinogen by the World Health Organization's International Agency for Research on Cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Evidence, however, has not supported a concern.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] There is no demonstrable link between mobile phone radiation and cancer risk.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Most cancers are non-hereditary (sporadic).
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Hereditary cancers are caused by inherited genetics.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Less than 0.3% of the population are carriers of a genetic mutation that has a large effect on cancer risk and these cause less than 3–10% of cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] The relative risk of developing colorectal cancer (the cancer with the highest mortality) when a first-degree relative (parent, sibling or child) has been diagnosed with it is about 2.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] The corresponding relative risk is 1.5 for lung cancer, and 1.9 for prostate cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] For breast cancer, the relative risk is 1.8 with a first-degree relative having developed it at 50 years of age or older, and 3.3 when the relative developed it when being younger than 50 years of age.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Taller people have an increased risk of cancer because they have more cells than shorter people.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Since height is genetically determined to a large extent, taller people have a heritable increase in cancer risk.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Some substances cause cancer primarily through their physical, rather than chemical, effects.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] A prominent example of this is prolonged exposure to asbestos, naturally occurring mineral fibers that are a major cause of mesothelioma (cancer of the serous membrane) usually the serous membrane surrounding the lungs.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Other substances in this category, including both naturally occurring and synthetic asbestos-like fibers, such as wollastonite, attapulgite, glass wool and rock wool, are believed to have similar effects.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Non-fibrous particulate materials that cause cancer include powdered metallic cobalt and nickel and crystalline silica (quartz, cristobalite and tridymite).
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Usually, physical carcinogens must get inside the body (such as through inhalation) and require years of exposure to produce cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Physical trauma resulting in cancer is relatively rare.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Claims that breaking bones resulted in bone cancer, for example, have not been proven.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Similarly, physical trauma is not accepted as a cause for cervical cancer, breast cancer or brain cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] One accepted source is frequent, long-term application of hot objects to the body.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] It is possible that repeated burns on the same part of the body, such as those produced by kanger and kairo heaters (charcoal hand warmers), may produce skin cancer, especially if carcinogenic chemicals are also present.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Frequent consumption of scalding hot tea may produce esophageal cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Generally, it is believed that cancer arises, or a pre-existing cancer is encouraged, during the process of healing, rather than directly by the trauma.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] However, repeated injuries to the same tissues might promote excessive cell proliferation, which could then increase the odds of a cancerous mutation.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Chronic inflammation has been hypothesized to directly cause mutation.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Inflammation can contribute to proliferation, survival, angiogenesis and migration of cancer cells by influencing the tumor microenvironment.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Oncogenes build up an inflammatory pro-tumorigenic microenvironment.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Hormones also play a role in the development of cancer by promoting cell proliferation.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Insulin-like growth factors and their binding proteins play a key role in cancer cell proliferation, differentiation and apoptosis, suggesting possible involvement in carcinogenesis.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Hormones are important agents in sex-related cancers, such as cancer of the breast, endometrium, prostate, ovary and testis and also of thyroid cancer and bone cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] For example, the daughters of women who have breast cancer have significantly higher levels of estrogen and progesterone than the daughters of women without breast cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] These higher hormone levels may explain their higher risk of breast cancer, even in the absence of a breast-cancer gene.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Similarly, men of African ancestry have significantly higher levels of testosterone than men of European ancestry and have a correspondingly higher level of prostate cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Men of Asian ancestry, with the lowest levels of testosterone-activating androstanediol glucuronide, have the lowest levels of prostate cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Other factors are relevant: obese people have higher levels of some hormones associated with cancer and a higher rate of those cancers.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Women who take hormone replacement therapy have a higher risk of developing cancers associated with those hormones.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] On the other hand, people who exercise far more than average have lower levels of these hormones and lower risk of cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Osteosarcoma may be promoted by growth hormones.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Some treatments and prevention approaches leverage this cause by artificially reducing hormone levels and thus discouraging hormone-sensitive cancers.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] There is an association between celiac disease and an increased risk of all cancers.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] People with untreated celiac disease have a higher risk, but this risk decreases with time after diagnosis and strict treatment.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] This may be due to the adoption of a gluten-free diet, which seems to have a protective role against the development of malignancy in people with celiac disease.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] However, the delay in diagnosis and initiation of a gluten-free diet seems to increase the risk of malignancies.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Rates of gastrointestinal cancers are increased in people with Crohn's disease and ulcerative colitis, due to chronic inflammation.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Immunomodulators and biologic agents used to treat these diseases may promote the development of extra-intestinal malignancies.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Cancer is fundamentally a disease of tissue growth regulation.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] For a normal cell to transform into a cancer cell, the genes that regulate cell growth and differentiation must be altered.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] The affected genes are divided into two broad categories.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Oncogenes are genes that promote cell growth and reproduction.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Tumor suppressor genes are genes that inhibit cell division and survival.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Malignant transformation can occur through the formation of novel oncogenes, the inappropriate over-expression of normal oncogenes, or by the under-expression or disabling of tumor suppressor genes.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Typically, changes in multiple genes are required to transform a normal cell into a cancer cell.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Genetic changes can occur at different levels and by different mechanisms.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] The gain or loss of an entire chromosome can occur through errors in mitosis.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] More common are mutations, which are changes in the nucleotide sequence of genomic DNA.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Large-scale mutations involve the deletion or gain of a portion of a chromosome.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Genomic amplification occurs when a cell gains copies (often 20 or more) of a small chromosomal locus, usually containing one or more oncogenes and adjacent genetic material.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Translocation occurs when two separate chromosomal regions become abnormally fused, often at a characteristic location.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] A well-known example of this is the Philadelphia chromosome, or translocation of chromosomes 9 and 22, which occurs in chronic myelogenous leukemia and results in production of the BCR-Abl fusion protein, an oncogenic tyrosine kinase.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Small-scale mutations include point mutations, deletions, and insertions, which may occur in the promoter region of a gene and affect its expression, or may occur in the gene's coding sequence and alter the function or stability of its protein product.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Disruption of a single gene may also result from integration of genomic material from a DNA virus or retrovirus, leading to the expression of *viral* oncogenes in the affected cell and its descendants.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Replication of the data contained within the DNA of living cells will probabilistically result in some errors (mutations).
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Complex error correction and prevention are built into the process and safeguard the cell against cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] If a significant error occurs, the damaged cell can self-destruct through programmed cell death, termed apoptosis.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] If the error control processes fail, then the mutations will survive and be passed along to daughter cells.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Some environments make errors more likely to arise and propagate.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Such environments can include the presence of disruptive substances called carcinogens, repeated physical injury, heat, ionising radiation, or hypoxia.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] The transformation of a normal cell into cancer is akin to a chain reaction caused by initial errors, which compound into more severe errors, each progressively allowing the cell to escape more controls that limit normal tissue growth.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] This rebellion-like scenario is an undesirable survival of the fittest, where the driving forces of evolution work against the body's design and enforcement of order.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Once cancer has begun to develop, this ongoing process, termed *clonal evolution*, drives progression towards more invasive stages.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Clonal evolution leads to intra-tumour heterogeneity (cancer cells with heterogeneous mutations) that complicates the design of effective treatments, as therapies must account for the selective pressures they exert on the tumour cell population.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] The classical view of cancer is a set of diseases driven by progressive genetic abnormalities that include mutations in tumor-suppressor genes and oncogenes, and in chromosomal abnormalities.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] A role for epigenetic alterations was identified in the early 21st century.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Epigenetic alterations are functionally relevant modifications to the genome that do not change the nucleotide sequence.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Examples of such modifications are changes in DNA methylation (hypermethylation and hypomethylation), histone modification and changes in chromosomal architecture (caused by inappropriate expression of proteins such as HMGA2 or HMGA1).
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Each of these alterations regulates gene expression without altering the underlying DNA sequence.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] These changes may remain through cell divisions, endure for multiple generations, and can be considered as equivalent to mutations.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Epigenetic alterations occur frequently in cancers.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] As an example, one study listed protein coding genes that were frequently altered in their methylation in association with colon cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] These included 147 hypermethylated and 27 hypomethylated genes.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Of the hypermethylated genes, 10 were hypermethylated in 100% of colon cancers and many others were hypermethylated in more than 50% of colon cancers.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] While epigenetic alterations are found in cancers, the epigenetic alterations in DNA repair genes, causing reduced expression of DNA repair proteins, may be of particular importance.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Such alterations may occur early in the progression to cancer and are a possible cause of the genetic instability characteristic of cancers.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Reduced expression of DNA repair genes disrupts DNA repair.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] This is shown in the figure at the 4th level from the top.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] (In the figure, red wording indicates the central role of DNA damage and defects in DNA repair in the progression to cancer.) When DNA repair is deficient DNA damage remains in cells at a higher than usual level (5th level) and causes increased frequencies of mutation and/or epimutation (6th level).
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Mutation rates increase substantially in cells defective in DNA mismatch repair or in homologous recombinational repair (HRR).
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Chromosomal rearrangements and aneuploidy (an abnormal number of chromosomes in a cell) also increase in HRR defective cells.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Higher levels of DNA damage cause increased mutation (right side of figure) and increased epimutation.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] During repair of DNA double strand breaks, or repair of other DNA damage, incompletely cleared repair sites can cause epigenetic gene silencing.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Deficient expression of DNA repair proteins due to an inherited mutation can increase cancer risks.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Individuals with an inherited impairment in any of 34 DNA repair genes (see article DNA repair-deficiency disorder) have increased cancer risk, with some defects ensuring a 100% lifetime chance of cancer (e.g. p53 mutations).
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Germline DNA repair mutations are noted on the figure's left side.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] However, such germline mutations (which cause highly penetrant cancer syndromes) are the cause of only about 1 percent of cancers.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] In sporadic cancers, deficiencies in DNA repair are occasionally caused by a mutation in a DNA repair gene but are much more frequently caused by epigenetic alterations that reduce or silence expression of DNA repair genes.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] This is indicated in the figure at the 3rd level.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Many studies of heavy metal-induced carcinogenesis show that such heavy metals cause a reduction in expression of DNA repair enzymes, some through epigenetic mechanisms.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] DNA repair inhibition is proposed to be a predominant mechanism in heavy metal-induced carcinogenicity.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] In addition, frequent epigenetic alterations of the DNA sequences code for small RNAs called microRNAs (or miRNAs). miRNAs do not code for proteins, but can "target" protein-coding genes and reduce their expression.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Cancers usually arise from an assemblage of mutations and epimutations that confer a selective advantage leading to clonal expansion (see Field defects in progression to cancer).
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Mutations, however, may not be as frequent in cancers as epigenetic alterations.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] An average cancer of the breast or colon can have about 60 to 70 protein-altering mutations, of which about three or four may be "driver" mutations and the remaining ones may be "passenger" mutations.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] The typical steps in metastasis are local invasion, intravasation (entry of cancer cells into a blood or lymph vessel), circulation through the body, extravasation (exit from the vessel into surrounding tissue), proliferation and angiogenesis (formation of new blood vessels to supply the tumour).
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Different types of cancers tend to metastasize to particular organs, but overall the most common places for metastases to occur are the lungs, liver, brain and the bones.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Normal cells typically generate about 30% of energy from glycolysis, whereas most cancers rely on glycolysis for energy production (Warburg effect).
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] But a minority of cancer types rely on oxidative phosphorylation as the primary energy source, including lymphoma, leukemia, and endometrial cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Even in these cases, however, the use of glycolysis as an energy source rarely exceeds 60%.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] A few cancers use glutamine as the major energy source, partly because it provides nitrogen required for nucleotide (DNA, RNA) synthesis.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Cancer stem cells often use oxidative phosphorylation or glutamine as a primary energy source.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Most cancers are initially recognized either because of the appearance of signs or symptoms or through screening.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Neither of these leads to a definitive diagnosis, which requires the examination of a tissue sample by a pathologist.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] People with suspected cancer are investigated with medical tests.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] These commonly include blood tests, X-rays, (contrast) CT scans and endoscopy.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] The tissue diagnosis from the biopsy indicates the type of cell that is proliferating, its histological grade, genetic abnormalities and other features.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Together, this information is useful to evaluate the prognosis and to choose the best treatment.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Cytogenetics and immunohistochemistry are other types of tissue tests.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] These tests provide information about molecular changes (such as mutations, fusion genes and numerical chromosome changes) and may thus also indicate the prognosis and best treatment.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Cancer diagnosis can cause psychological distress and psychosocial interventions, such as talking therapy, may help people with this.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Some people choose to disclose the diagnosis widely; others prefer to keep the information private, especially shortly after the diagnosis, or to disclose it only partially or to selected people.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Cancers are classified by the type of cell that the tumor cells resemble and is therefore presumed to be the origin of the tumor.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Cancers are usually named using *-carcinoma*, *-sarcoma* or *-blastoma* as a suffix, with the Latin or Greek word for the organ or tissue of origin as the root.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] For example, cancers of the liver parenchyma arising from malignant epithelial cells is called *hepatocarcinoma*, while a malignancy arising from primitive liver precursor cells is called a hepatoblastoma and a cancer arising from fat cells is called a *liposarcoma*.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] For some common cancers, the English organ name is used.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] For example, the most common type of breast cancer is called *ductal carcinoma of the breast*.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Here, the adjective *ductal* refers to the appearance of cancer under the microscope, which suggests that it has originated in the milk ducts.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Benign tumors (which are not cancers) are named using *-oma* as a suffix with the organ name as the root.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] For example, a benign tumor of smooth muscle cells is called a *leiomyoma* (the common name of this frequently occurring benign tumor in the uterus is *fibroid*).
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Confusingly, some types of cancer use the *-noma* suffix, examples including melanoma and seminoma.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Some types of cancer are named for the size and shape of the cells under a microscope, such as giant cell carcinoma, spindle cell carcinoma and small-cell carcinoma.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Cancer prevention involves changes on the individual level, as well as the public policy level.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Around 40% of cancer can be prevented by avoiding or eliminating risk factors.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Cancer prevention is more cost-effective than treatment.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] On an individual level, cancer can be prevented by avoiding carcinogens such as with smoking, limiting sun exposure, maintaining a healthy weight and active lifestyle, and following medical guidance designed to decrease risk for cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Public policy changes are required to expand individual access to cancer prevention interventions, as well as to address collective issues that cause cancer such as air pollution.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Due to having shared causes in common, efforts to prevent cancer often help prevent other diseases as well as improve the environment.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Cancer prevention through diet generally emphasizes broad, healthy eating habits over focusing on specific foods.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] The risk for cancer is decreased with a diet high in fiber, fruits and vegetables, and low in red and processed meat.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Replacing refined sugars with whole grains, and consuming plant-based proteins and fats also helps reduce the risk of cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Maintaining a healthy body weight and being physically active helps prevent cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Obesity increases the risk for cancer, partly through causing inflammation and metabolic and hormonal abnormalities.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Exercise promotes healthy immune and hormonal systems that reduce cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Diets high in calcium (such as dairy products) and coffee, and low in processed meat, can help prevent colorectal cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Alcohol is a group 1 carcinogen, and is responsible for around 4% of all cancer deaths.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Any amount of alcohol increases the risk for cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Alcohol causes several types of cancer, through different mechanisms including the breakdown of ethanol into acetaldehyde, which damages DNA.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Alcohol increases estrogen, which contributes to the development of breast cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Alcohol acts as a solvent for some carcinogens, allowing them to penetrate cells more easily.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] For instance, consuming alcohol along with tobacco helps carcinogens in tobacco penetrate the cells of the mouth and cause mouth cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Smoking is the number one preventable cause of cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Smoking causes at least 20 different types of cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Cigars, pipes (including water pipes), and smokeless tobacco cause cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] More than 1.2 million people die every year from exposure to second-hand smoke, around 100,000 of these deaths from cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] The health impact of electronic cigarettes (vaping) and similar products is unknown and subject to debate.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Breastfeeding reduces the mother's risk for developing breast cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Infants who breastfed are less likely to gain excess weight later in life.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] A healthy weight helps to reduce the risk for several types of cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Ultraviolet radiation is the main cause of skin cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] The incidence of skin cancer is increasing, and it is the most common type of cancer in lighter-skinned populations.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] UV radiation, whether from sunlight or tanning beds, directly and indirectly damages DNA.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] The most effective way to prevent skin cancer is to limit sun exposure and not use tanning beds, wear protective clothing (such as a hat), wear sunscreen, and make use of the shade.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] The best time to avoid sunlight is between 9:00 a.m. and 3:00 p.m. when UV radiation is strongest.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Even on cloudy days about 80% of UV radiation is still present.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] UV radiation does not correlate with temperature—there is just as much UV radiation from the sun on a cold day as on a hot day.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] About 10% of UVB radiation passes through glass windows.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] UV exposure during childhood is particularly harmful.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] However, the beneficial effects of sunlight exposure (such as the production of vitamin D) can be achieved while avoiding harmful amounts of sun exposure.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] The ozone layer absorbs UV radiation from the sun, reducing rates of skin cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] However, atmospheric pollution has decreased the ozone layer, and increased rates of skin cancer globally.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] In 1987, an international treaty named the Montreal Protocol was signed to limit the release of ozone-damaging chemicals.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Since then the ozone layer has been recovering, and it is expected that by 2100 the Montreal Protocol will have prevented 11 million cases of melanoma in the United States.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Air pollution, both outdoor and indoor, is the largest environmental contributor to cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Air pollution caused an estimated 350,167 deaths from lung cancer in 2017.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Airborne particulate matter smaller than 2.5 µm (PM2.5) is a group 1 carcinogen.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] The concentration of PM2.5 in the air is the most reliable predictor of how carcinogenic the air is.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] PM2.5 primarily comes from the burning of fuel for transportation, power generation, and industry, the burning of biomass (e.g. forest fires, stubble burning), and heating and cooking in the home.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] In 2017, an estimated 14.1% of all lung cancer deaths were caused by PM2.5 pollution.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Local PM2.5 and PM10 levels can be monitored online, and wearing a close-fitting particulate respirator reduces personal exposure when levels are high.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Exposure to cancer-causing air pollution can also be reduced by avoiding motorized transportation, selecting routes away from pollution sources such as coal plants, and keeping vehicle windows closed in heavy traffic.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Decreasing outdoor air pollution requires action on the public policy level, and involves international collaborative efforts.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Indoor air pollution includes PM2.5 from the burning of fuels, as well as other pollutants such as radon and hazardous construction materials (e.g. asbestos, glues, formaldehyde, lead).
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] In 2019, the percent of preventable cases of lung cancer by cause was estimated as 62% for smoking, 15% for PM2.5 in outdoor air, 5.8% for secondhand smoke, 4% from using solid fuels for cooking, and 4% for radon.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Individuals can decrease air pollution in the home by using clean fuels, maintaining adequate ventilation, and using air purifiers.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Around 80% of ionizing radiation that people are exposed to comes from natural sources, around half of which comes from breathing in radioactive radon gas.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Radon is produced by the decay of uranium in the ground, becoming a radioactive gas that can accumulate in the buildings above it.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Exposure to radon can be reduced by testing homes and, when found to be high, taking steps to reduce indoor radon levels.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] The primary method to reduce indoor radon levels is a vent pipe system and fan, which pulls radon from beneath the building and vents it to the outside.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Around 20% of ionizing radiation that people are exposed to comes from artificial sources, primarily from x-rays used for medical imaging.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] CT scans, which take x-rays at many angles to produce a 3D image, expose patients to a higher level of radiation than standard 2D x-rays.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Cancer prevention focuses on avoiding unnecessary diagnostic procedures, and minimizing the dose of ionizing radiation that patients are exposed to during these procedures.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] There have been 38 workplace chemicals and 12 workplace circumstances classified as carcinogenic, and 41 chemicals and 6 circumstances classified as probably carcinogenic.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Despite being known to cause cancer, workers are still commonly exposed to silica, diesel engine exhaust, heavy metals, asbestos, and polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Occupational cancer can be reduced, and in recent decades successful regulations and programs have reduced or eliminated exposure to certain carcinogens in the workplace.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Prevention involves decreasing the use of certain chemicals and if this isn't possible limiting exposure to these substances, a process known as hierarchy of controls.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Occupational cancer can also be prevented by improving workplace procedures and training, and by using personal protective equipment.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] In 2018, 2.2 million cases of cancer were caused by infection, primarily by *Helicobacter pylori* (810,000), human papillomavirus (690,000), hepatitis B (360,000), and hepatitis C (160,000).
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] All four of these infections can either be vaccinated against or treated, and collectively they cause more than 90% of infection-related cancers worldwide.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Medications can be used to prevent cancer in a few circumstances.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] In the general population, NSAIDs reduce the risk of colorectal cancer; however, due to cardiovascular and gastrointestinal side effects, they cause more harm than benefit when used for prevention.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Aspirin is not recommended for reducing cancer risk.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] COX-2 inhibitors may decrease the rate of polyp formation in people with familial adenomatous polyposis; however, it is associated with the same adverse effects as NSAIDs.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Women who have an increased risk for breast cancer can lower their chances of getting breast cancer by taking tamoxifen, raloxifene, or aromatase inhibitors.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] No vitamin, multivitamin, or nutritional supplement is recommended for the prevention of cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Vitamin E supplements do not prevent cancer, and beta-carotene supplements increase the odds of lung cancer in those already at a high risk for it.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Hormone-sensitive cancers are dependent on hormones for growth and survival.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Medications that effect hormone levels may therefore have a harmful or beneficial effect on cancer rates.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Women who are on, or recently took, combined oral contraceptives (COCs) have an increased risk for breast cancer and cervical cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] However, CBCs also decrease the risk for ovarian cancer, and this protective effect continues years after stopping their use.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Estrogen-only menopausal hormone therapy increases the risk of breast, endometrial, and ovarian cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p01] Combined estrogen–progestogen hormone therapy increases the risk of breast and endometrial cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Unlike diagnostic efforts prompted by symptoms and medical signs, cancer screening involves efforts to detect cancer after it has formed, but before any noticeable symptoms appear.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] This may involve physical examination, blood or urine tests or medical imaging.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Cancer screening is not available for many types of cancers.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Even when tests are available, they may not be recommended for everyone.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] *Universal screening* or *mass screening* involves screening everyone.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] *Selective screening* identifies people who are at higher risk, such as people with a family history.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Several factors are considered to determine whether the benefits of screening outweigh the risks and the costs of screening.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Screens for gastric cancer using photofluorography due to the high incidence there.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Genetic testing for individuals at high risk of certain cancers is recommended by unofficial groups.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Carriers of these mutations may then undergo enhanced surveillance, chemoprevention, or preventative surgery to reduce their subsequent risk.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Many treatment options for cancer exist.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] The primary ones include surgery, chemotherapy, radiation therapy, hormonal therapy, targeted therapy and palliative care.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Which treatments are used depends on the type, location and grade of the cancer as well as the patient's health and preferences.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] The treatment intent may or may not be curative.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Chemotherapy is the treatment of cancer with one or more cytotoxic anti-neoplastic drugs (chemotherapeutic agents) as part of a standardized regimen.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] The term encompasses a variety of drugs, which are divided into broad categories such as alkylating agents and antimetabolites.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Traditional chemotherapeutic agents act by killing cells that divide rapidly, a critical property of most cancer cells.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] It was found that providing combined cytotoxic drugs is better than a single drug, a process called the combination therapy, which has an advantage in the statistics of survival and response to the tumor and in the progress of the disease.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] A Cochrane review concluded that combined therapy was more effective in treating metastasized breast cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] However, generally it is not certain whether combination chemotherapy leads to better health outcomes, when both survival and toxicity are considered.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Targeted therapy is a form of chemotherapy that targets specific molecular differences between cancer and normal cells.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] The first targeted therapies blocked the estrogen receptor molecule, inhibiting the growth of breast cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Another common example is the class of Bcr-Abl inhibitors, which are used to treat chronic myelogenous leukemia (CML).
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Currently, targeted therapies exist for many of the most common cancer types, including bladder cancer, breast cancer, colorectal cancer, kidney cancer, leukemia, liver cancer, lung cancer, lymphoma, pancreatic cancer, prostate cancer, skin cancer, and thyroid cancer as well as other cancer types.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] The efficacy of chemotherapy depends on the type of cancer and the stage.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] In combination with surgery, chemotherapy has proven useful in cancer types including breast cancer, colorectal cancer, pancreatic cancer, osteogenic sarcoma, testicular cancer, ovarian cancer and certain lung cancers.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Chemotherapy is curative for some cancers, such as some leukemias, ineffective in some brain tumors, and needless in others, such as most non-melanoma skin cancers.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] The effectiveness of chemotherapy is often limited by its toxicity to other tissues in the body.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Even when chemotherapy does not provide a permanent cure, it may be useful to reduce symptoms such as pain or to reduce the size of an inoperable tumor in the hope that surgery will become possible in the future.*Wang M, Zhang C, Yang G, Shi Y (March 2017).
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] "Neoadjuvant Chemotherapy Creates Surgery Opportunities For Inoperable Locally Advanced Breast Cancer".
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Radiation therapy involves the use of ionizing radiation in an attempt to either cure or improve symptoms.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] It works by damaging the DNA of cancerous tissue, causing mitotic catastrophe resulting in the death of the cancer cells.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] To spare normal tissues (such as skin or organs, which radiation must pass through to treat the tumor), shaped radiation beams are aimed from multiple exposure angles to intersect at the tumor, providing a much larger dose there than in the surrounding, healthy tissue.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] As with chemotherapy, cancers vary in their response to radiation therapy.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Radiation therapy is used in about half of cases.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] The radiation can be either from internal sources (brachytherapy) or external sources.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] The radiation is most commonly low energy X-rays for treating skin cancers, while higher energy X-rays are used for cancers within the body.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Radiation is typically used in addition to surgery and/or chemotherapy.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] For certain types of cancer, such as early head and neck cancer, it may be used alone.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Radiation therapy after surgery for brain metastases has been shown to not improve overall survival in patients compared to surgery alone.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] For painful bone metastasis, radiation therapy has been found to be effective in about 70% of patients.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Surgery is the primary method of treatment for most isolated, solid cancers and may play a role in palliation and prolongation of survival.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] It is typically an important part of the definitive diagnosis and staging of tumors, as biopsies are usually required.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] In localized cancer, surgery typically attempts to remove the entire mass along with, in certain cases, the lymph nodes in the area.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] For some types of cancer this is sufficient to eliminate the cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Palliative care may be confused with hospice and therefore only indicated when people approach end of life.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Like hospice care, palliative care attempts to help the patient cope with their immediate needs and to increase comfort.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Unlike hospice care, palliative care does not require people to stop treatment aimed at the cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Multiple national medical guidelines recommend early palliative care for patients whose cancer has produced distressing symptoms or who need help coping with their illness.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] In patients first diagnosed with metastatic disease, palliative care may be immediately indicated.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Palliative care is indicated for patients with a prognosis of less than 12 months of life even given aggressive treatment.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] A variety of therapies using immunotherapy, stimulating or helping the immune system to fight cancer, have come into use since 1997.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Laser therapy uses high-intensity light to treat cancer by shrinking or destroying tumors or precancerous growths.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Lasers are most commonly used to treat superficial cancers that are on the surface of the body or the lining of internal organs.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] It is used to treat basal cell skin cancer and the very early stages of others like cervical, penile, vaginal, vulvar, and non-small cell lung cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] It is often combined with other treatments, such as surgery, chemotherapy, or radiation therapy.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Laser-induced interstitial thermotherapy (LITT), or interstitial laser photocoagulation, uses lasers to treat some cancers using hyperthermia, which uses heat to shrink tumors by damaging or killing cancer cells.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Lasers are more precise than surgery and cause less damage, pain, bleeding, swelling, and scarring.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] A disadvantage is that surgeons must have specialized training.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] It may be more expensive than other treatments.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Complementary and alternative cancer treatments are a diverse group of therapies, practices and products that are not part of conventional medicine.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] "Complementary medicine" refers to methods and substances used along with conventional medicine, while "alternative medicine" refers to compounds used instead of conventional medicine.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Most complementary and alternative medicines for cancer have not been studied or tested using conventional techniques such as clinical trials.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Some alternative treatments have been investigated and shown to be ineffective but still continue to be marketed and promoted.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Survival rates vary by cancer type and by the stage at which it is diagnosed, ranging from majority survival to complete mortality five years after diagnosis.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Once a cancer has metastasized, prognosis normally becomes much worse.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] About half of patients receiving treatment for invasive cancer (excluding carcinoma *in situ* and non-melanoma skin cancers) die from that cancer or its treatment.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] A majority of cancer deaths are due to metastases of the primary tumor.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Survival is worse in the developing world, partly because the types of cancer that are most common there are harder to treat than those associated with developed countries.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Those who survive cancer develop a second primary cancer at about twice the rate of those never diagnosed.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Predicting short- or long-term survival depends on many factors.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] The most important are the cancer type and the patient's age and overall health.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Those who are frail with other health problems have lower survival rates than otherwise healthy people.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Centenarians are unlikely to survive for five years even if treatment is successful.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] People who report a higher quality of life tend to survive longer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] People with lower quality of life may be affected by depression and other complications and/or disease progression that both impairs quality and quantity of life.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Additionally, patients with worse prognoses may be depressed or report poorer quality of life because they perceive that their condition is likely to be fatal.*Satin JR, Linden W, Phillips MJ (November 2009).
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] "Depression as a predictor of disease progression and mortality in cancer patients: a meta-analysis".
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] People with cancer have an increased risk of blood clots in their veins which can be life-threatening.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] The use of blood thinners such as heparin decrease the risk of blood clots but have not been shown to increase survival in people with cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] People who take blood thinners also have an increased risk of bleeding.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Although extremely rare, some forms of cancer, even from an advanced stage, can heal spontaneously.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] This phenomenon is known as spontaneous remission.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Estimates are that in 2018, 18.1 million new cases of cancer and 9.6 million deaths occur globally.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] About 20% of males and 17% of females will get cancer at some point in time while 13% of males and 9% of females will die from it.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] In 2008, approximately 12.7 million cancers were diagnosed (excluding non-melanoma skin cancers and other non-invasive cancers) and in 2010 nearly 7.98 million people died.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Cancers account for almost one in six deaths.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] The cancers causing the most deaths, as of 2020 are lung cancer (1.8 million), colorectal cancer (916,000), liver cancer (830,000), stomach cancer (769,000) and breast cancer (685,000).
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] This makes invasive cancer the leading cause of death in the developed world and the second leading in the developing world.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Over half of these cases occur in the developing world.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Deaths from cancer were 5.8 million in 1990.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Deaths have been increasing primarily due to longer lifespans and lifestyle changes in the developing world.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] The most significant risk factor for developing cancer is age.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Although it is possible for cancer to strike at any age, most patients with invasive cancer are over 65.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] According to cancer researcher Robert A.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Weinberg, "If we lived long enough, sooner or later we all would get cancer." Some of the association between aging and cancer is attributed to immunosenescence, errors accumulated in DNA over a lifetime and age-related changes in the endocrine system.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Aging's effect on cancer is complicated by factors such as DNA damage and inflammation promoting it and factors such as vascular aging and endocrine changes inhibiting it.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Some slow-growing cancers are particularly common, but often are not fatal.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Autopsy studies in Europe and Asia showed that up to 36% of people have undiagnosed and apparently harmless thyroid cancer at the time of their deaths and that 80% of men develop prostate cancer by age 80.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] As these cancers do not cause the patient's death, identifying them would have represented overdiagnosis rather than useful medical care.*Lowenstein LM, Basourakos SP, Williams MD, Troncoso P, Gregg JR, Thompson TC, et al.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] "Active surveillance for prostate and thyroid cancers: evolution in clinical paradigms and lessons learned".
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] The three most common childhood cancers are leukemia (34%), brain tumors (23%) and lymphomas (12%).
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] In the United States, cancer affects about 1 in 285 children.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Rates of childhood cancer increased by 0.6% per year between 1975 and 2002 in the United States and by 1.1% per year between 1978 and 1997 in Europe.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Death from childhood cancer decreased by half between 1975 and 2010 in the United States.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Cancer has existed for all of human history.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] The earliest written record regarding cancer is from c.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] 1600 BC in the Egyptian Edwin Smith Papyrus and describes breast cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] 370 BC) described several kinds of cancer, referring to them with the Greek word καρκίνος *karkinos* (crab or crayfish).
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] This name comes from the appearance of the cut surface of a solid malignant tumor, with "the veins stretched on all sides as the animal the crab has its feet, whence it derives its name".
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Galen stated that "cancer of the breast is so called because of the fancied resemblance to a crab given by the lateral prolongations of the tumor and the adjacent distended veins".
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] 25 BC – 50 AD) translated *karkinos* into Latin as *cancer*, also meaning crab and recommended surgery as treatment.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Galen (2nd century AD) disagreed with the use of surgery and recommended purgatives instead.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] These recommendations largely stood for 1000 years.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] In the 15th, 16th and 17th centuries, it became acceptable for doctors to dissect bodies to discover the cause of death.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] The German professor Wilhelm Fabry believed that breast cancer was caused by a milk clot in a mammary duct.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] The Dutch professor Francois de la Boe Sylvius, a follower of Descartes, believed that all disease was the outcome of chemical processes and that acidic lymph fluid was the cause of cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] His contemporary Nicolaes Tulp believed that cancer was a poison that slowly spreads and concluded that it was contagious.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] The physician John Hill described tobacco sniffing as the cause of nose cancer in 1761.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] This was followed by the report in 1775 by British surgeon Percivall Pott that chimney sweeps' carcinoma, a cancer of the scrotum, was a common disease among chimney sweeps.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] With the widespread use of the microscope in the 18th century, it was discovered that the 'cancer poison' spread from the primary tumor through the lymph nodes to other sites ("metastasis").
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] This view of the disease was first formulated by the English surgeon Campbell De Morgan between 1871 and 1874.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Although many diseases (such as heart failure) may have a worse prognosis than most cases of cancer, cancer is the subject of widespread fear and taboos.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] The euphemism of "a long illness" to describe cancers leading to death is still commonly used in obituaries, rather than naming the disease explicitly, reflecting an apparent stigma.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Cancer is also euphemised as "the C-word"; Macmillan Cancer Support uses the term to try to lessen the fear around the disease.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] In Nigeria, one local name for cancer translates into English as "the disease that cannot be cured".
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Western conceptions of patients' rights for people with cancer include a duty to fully disclose the medical situation to the person, and the right to engage in shared decision-making in a way that respects the person's own values.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] In other cultures, other rights and values are preferred.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] For example, most African cultures value whole families rather than individualism.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] In parts of Africa, a diagnosis is commonly made so late that cure is not possible, and treatment, if available at all, would quickly bankrupt the family.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] As a result of these factors, African healthcare providers tend to let family members decide whether, when and how to disclose the diagnosis, and they tend to do so slowly and circuitously, as the person shows interest and an ability to cope with the grim news.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] People from Asian and South American countries also tend to prefer a slower, less candid approach to disclosure than is idealized in the United States and Western Europe, and they believe that sometimes it would be preferable not to be told about a cancer diagnosis.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] In general, disclosure of the diagnosis is more common than it was in the 20th century, but full disclosure of the prognosis is not offered to many patients around the world.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] In the United States and some other cultures, cancer is regarded as a disease that must be "fought" to end the "civil insurrection"; a war on cancer was declared in the US.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Military metaphors are particularly common in descriptions of cancer's human effects, and they emphasize both the state of the patient's health and the need to take immediate, decisive actions himself rather than to delay, to ignore or to rely entirely on others.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] The military metaphors also help rationalize radical, destructive treatments.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] In the 1970s, a relatively popular alternative cancer treatment in the US was a specialized form of talk therapy, based on the idea that cancer was caused by a bad attitude.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] People with a "cancer personality"—depressed, repressed, self-loathing and afraid to express their emotions—were believed to have manifested cancer through subconscious desire.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Some psychotherapists claimed that treatment to change the patient's outlook on life would cure the cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Among other effects, this belief allowed society to blame the victim for having caused the cancer (by "wanting" it) or having prevented its cure (by not becoming a sufficiently happy, fearless and loving person).
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] It also increased patients' anxiety, as they incorrectly believed that natural emotions of sadness, anger or fear shorten their lives.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] The idea was ridiculed by Susan Sontag, who published *Illness as Metaphor* while recovering from treatment for breast cancer in 1978.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Although the original idea is now generally regarded as nonsense, the idea partly persists in a reduced form with a widespread, but incorrect, belief that deliberately cultivating a habit of positive thinking will increase survival.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] This notion is particularly strong in breast cancer culture.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] One idea about why people with cancer are blamed or stigmatized, called the just-world fallacy, is that blaming cancer on the patient's actions or attitudes allows the blamers to regain a sense of control.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] This is based upon the blamers' belief that the world is fundamentally just and so any dangerous illness, like cancer, must be a type of punishment for bad choices, because in a just world, bad things would not happen to good people.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] The total health care expenditure on cancer in the US was estimated to be $80.2 billion in 2015.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Even though cancer-related health care expenditure have increased in absolute terms during recent decades, the share of health expenditure devoted to cancer treatment has remained close to 5% between the 1960s and 2004.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] A similar pattern has been observed in Europe where about 6% of all health care expenditure are spent on cancer treatment.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] In addition to health care expenditure and financial toxicity, cancer causes indirect costs in the form of productivity losses due to sick days, permanent incapacity and disability as well as premature death during working age.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Cancer causes also costs for informal care.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Indirect costs and informal care costs are typically estimated to exceed or equal the health care costs of cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] A study found women were around six times more likely to be divorced soon after a diagnosis of cancer compared to men.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Rate of separation for cancer-survivors showed correlations with race, age, income, and comorbidities in a study.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] A review found a somewhat decreased divorce rate for most cancer types, and noted study heterogeneity and methodological weaknesses for many studies on the effects of cancer on divorce.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Because cancer is a class of diseases, it is unlikely that there will ever be a single "cure for cancer" any more than there will be a single treatment for all infectious diseases.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Angiogenesis inhibitors were once incorrectly thought to have potential as a "silver bullet" treatment applicable to many types of cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Angiogenesis inhibitors and other cancer therapeutics are used in combination to reduce cancer morbidity and mortality.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Experimental cancer treatments are studied in clinical trials to compare the proposed treatment to the best existing treatment.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Treatments that succeeded in one cancer type can be tested against other types.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Diagnostic tests are under development to better target the right therapies to the right patients, based on their individual biology.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] The improved understanding of molecular biology and cellular biology due to cancer research has led to new treatments for cancer since US President Richard Nixon declared the "war on cancer" in 1971.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Since then, the country has spent over $200 billion on cancer research, including resources from public and private sectors.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] The cancer death rate (adjusting for size and age of the population) declined by five percent between 1950 and 2005.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Competition for financial resources appears to have suppressed the creativity, cooperation, risk-taking and original thinking required to make fundamental discoveries, unduly favoring low-risk research into small incremental advancements over riskier, more innovative research.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Other consequences of competition appear to be many studies with dramatic claims whose results cannot be replicated and perverse incentives that encourage grantee institutions to grow without making sufficient investments in their own faculty and facilities.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Virotherapy, which uses oncolytic viruses, is being studied.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] In the wake of the COVID-19 pandemic, there has been a worry that cancer research and treatment are slowing down.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Cancer affects approximately 1 in 1,000 pregnant women.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] The most common cancers found during pregnancy are the same as the most common cancers found in non-pregnant women during childbearing ages: breast cancer, cervical cancer, leukemia, lymphoma, melanoma, ovarian cancer and colorectal cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Diagnosing a new cancer in a pregnant woman is difficult, in part because any symptoms are commonly assumed to be a normal discomfort associated with pregnancy.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] As a result, cancer is typically discovered at a somewhat later stage than average.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Some imaging procedures, such as MRIs (magnetic resonance imaging), CT scans, ultrasounds and mammograms with fetal shielding are considered safe during pregnancy; some others, such as PET scans, are not.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Treatment is generally the same as for non-pregnant women.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] However, radiation and radioactive drugs are normally avoided during pregnancy, especially if the fetal dose might exceed 100 cGy.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] In some cases, some or all treatments are postponed until after birth if the cancer is diagnosed late in the pregnancy.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Early deliveries are often used to advance the start of treatment.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Surgery is generally safe, but pelvic surgeries during the first trimester may cause miscarriage.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Some treatments, especially certain chemotherapy drugs given during the first trimester, increase the risk of birth defects and pregnancy loss (spontaneous abortions and stillbirths).
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Elective abortions are not required and, for the most common forms and stages of cancer, do not improve the mother's survival.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] In a few instances, such as advanced uterine cancer, the pregnancy cannot be continued and in others, the patient may end the pregnancy so that she can begin aggressive chemotherapy.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Some treatments can interfere with the mother's ability to give birth vaginally or to breastfeed.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Cervical cancer may require birth by Caesarean section.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Radiation to the breast reduces the ability of that breast to produce milk and increases the risk of mastitis.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Also, when chemotherapy is given after birth, many of the drugs appear in breast milk, which could harm the baby.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Veterinary oncology, concentrating mainly on cats and dogs, is a growing specialty in wealthy countries and the major forms of human treatment such as surgery and radiotherapy may be offered.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] The most common types of cancer differ, but the cancer burden seems at least as high in pets as in humans.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Animals, typically rodents, are often used in cancer research and studies of natural cancers in larger animals may benefit research into human cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Across wild animals, there is still limited data on cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] Nonetheless, a study published in 2022, explored cancer risk in (non-domesticated) zoo mammals, belonging to 191 species for a total of 110,148 individuals, demonstrated that cancer is a ubiquitous disease of mammals and it can emerge anywhere along the mammalian phylogeny.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] This research also highlighted that cancer risk is not uniformly distributed along mammals.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] For instance, species in the order Carnivora are particularly prone to be affected by cancer (e.g. over 25% of clouded leopards, bat-eared foxes and red wolves die of cancer), while ungulates (especially even-toed ungulates) appear to face consistently low cancer risks.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] In non-humans, a few types of transmissible cancer have also been described, wherein the cancer spreads between animals by transmission of the tumor cells themselves.
[src:cancer-biology/cancer-p02] This phenomenon is seen in dogs with Sticker's sarcoma (also known as canine transmissible venereal tumor), and in Tasmanian devils with devil facial tumour disease (DFTD).
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Variants of inherited genes may predispose individuals to cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] In addition, environmental factors such as carcinogens and radiation cause mutations that may contribute to the development of cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Finally random mistakes in normal DNA replication may result in cancer-causing mutations.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] A series of several mutations to certain classes of genes is usually required before a normal cell will transform into a cancer cell.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Mutations in genes that regulate cell division, apoptosis (cell death), and DNA repair may result in uncontrolled cell proliferation and cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Cancer is fundamentally a disease of regulation of tissue growth.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] In order for a normal cell to transform into a cancer cell, genes that regulate cell growth and differentiation must be altered.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Genetic and epigenetic changes can occur at many levels, from gain or loss of entire chromosomes, to a mutation affecting a single DNA nucleotide, or to silencing or activating a microRNA that controls expression of 100 to 500 genes.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] There are two broad categories of genes that are affected by these changes.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Oncogenes may be normal genes that are expressed at inappropriately high levels, or altered genes that have novel properties.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] In either case, expression of these genes promotes the malignant phenotype of cancer cells.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Tumor suppressor genes are genes that inhibit cell division, survival, or other properties of cancer cells.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Tumor suppressor genes are often disabled by cancer-promoting genetic changes.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Finally Oncovirinae, viruses that contain an oncogene, are categorized as oncogenic because they trigger the growth of tumorous tissues in the host.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] This process is also referred to as viral transformation.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] It is also believed that cancer is caused due to chromosomal abnormalities as explained in chromosome theory of cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] There is a diverse classification scheme for the various genomic changes that may contribute to the generation of cancer cells.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Many of these changes are mutations, or changes in the nucleotide sequence of genomic DNA.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] There are also many epigenetic changes that alter whether genes are expressed or not expressed.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Aneuploidy, the presence of an abnormal number of chromosomes, is one genomic change that is not a mutation, and may involve either gain or loss of one or more chromosomes through errors in mitosis.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Large-scale mutations involve either the deletion or duplication of a portion of a chromosome.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Genomic amplification occurs when a cell gains many copies (often 20 or more) of a small chromosomal region, usually containing one or more oncogenes and adjacent genetic material.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] A well-known example of this is the Philadelphia chromosome, or translocation of chromosomes 9 and 22, which occurs in chronic myelogenous leukemia, and results in production of the BCR-abl fusion protein, an oncogenic tyrosine kinase.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Small-scale mutations include point mutations, deletions, and insertions, which may occur in the promoter of a gene and affect its expression, or may occur in the gene's coding sequence and alter the function or stability of its protein product.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Disruption of a single gene may also result from integration of genomic material from a DNA virus or retrovirus, and such an event may also result in the expression of viral oncogenes in the affected cell and its descendants.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] DNA damage is considered to be the primary cause of cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] More than 60,000 new naturally occurring instances of DNA damage arise, on average, per human cell, per day, due to endogenous cellular processes (see article DNA damage (naturally occurring)).
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Additional DNA damage can arise from exposure to exogenous agents.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] As one example of an exogenous carcinogenic agent, tobacco smoke causes increased DNA damage, and this DNA damage likely cause the increase of lung cancer due to smoking.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] DNA damage can also be caused by substances produced in the body.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Macrophages and neutrophils in an inflamed colonic epithelium are the source of reactive oxygen species causing the DNA damage that initiates colonic tumorigenesis, and bile acids, at high levels in the colons of humans eating a high-fat diet, also cause DNA damage and contribute to colon cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Such exogenous and endogenous sources of DNA damage are indicated in the boxes at the top of the figure in this section.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] The central role of DNA damage in progression to cancer is indicated at the second level of the figure.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] The central elements of DNA damage, epigenetic alterations and deficient DNA repair in progression to cancer are shown in red.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] A deficiency in DNA repair would cause more DNA damage to accumulate, and increase the risk for cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] For example, individuals with an inherited impairment in any of 34 DNA repair genes (see article DNA repair-deficiency disorder) are at increased risk of cancer, with some defects causing an up to 100% lifetime chance of cancer (e.g. p53 mutations).
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Such germline mutations are shown in a box at the left of the figure, with an indication of their contribution to DNA repair deficiency.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] However, such germline mutations (which cause highly penetrant cancer syndromes) are the cause of only about *one percent* of cancers.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] The majority of cancers are called non-hereditary or "sporadic cancers".
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] About 30% of sporadic cancers do have some hereditary component that is currently undefined, while the majority, or 70% of sporadic cancers, have no hereditary component.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] In sporadic cancers, a deficiency in DNA repair is occasionally due to a mutation in a DNA repair gene; much more frequently, reduced or absent expression of DNA repair genes is due to epigenetic alterations that reduce or silence gene expression.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] This is indicated in the figure at the 3rd level from the top.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] For example, for 113 colorectal cancers examined in sequence, only four had a missense mutation in the DNA repair gene MGMT, while the majority had reduced MGMT expression due to methylation of the MGMT promoter region (an epigenetic alteration).
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] When expression of DNA repair genes is reduced, this causes a DNA repair deficiency.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] With a DNA repair deficiency, DNA damage persists in cells at a higher than typical level (5th level from the top in figure); this excess damage causes an increased frequency of mutation and/or epimutation (6th level from top of figure).
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Experimentally, mutation rates increase substantially in cells defective in DNA mismatch repair or in homologous recombinational repair (HRR).
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Chromosomal rearrangements and aneuploidy also increase in HRR-defective cells.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] During repair of DNA double-strand breaks, or repair of other DNA damage, incompletely cleared repair sites can cause epigenetic gene silencing.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] The somatic mutations and epigenetic alterations caused by DNA damage and deficiencies in DNA repair accumulate in field defects.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Field defects are normal-appearing tissues with multiple alterations (discussed in the section below), and are common precursors to development of the disordered and over-proliferating clone of tissue in a cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Such field defects (second level from bottom of figure) may have numerous mutations and epigenetic alterations.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] It is impossible to determine the initial cause for most specific cancers.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] In a few cases, only one cause exists: for example, the virus HHV-8 causes all Kaposi's sarcomas.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] However, with the help of cancer epidemiology techniques and information, it is possible to produce an estimate of a likely cause in many more situations.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] For example, lung cancer has several causes, including tobacco use and radon gas.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] These statistical correlations have made it possible for researchers to infer that certain substances or behaviors are carcinogenic.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Tobacco smoke causes increased exogenous DNA damage, and this DNA damage is the likely cause of lung cancer due to smoking.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Among the more than 5,000 compounds in tobacco smoke, the genotoxic DNA-damaging agents that occur both at the highest concentrations, and which have the strongest mutagenic effects are acrolein, formaldehyde, acrylonitrile, 1,3-butadiene, acetaldehyde, ethylene oxide and isoprene.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Using molecular biological techniques, it is possible to characterize the mutations, epimutations or chromosomal aberrations within a tumor, and rapid progress is being made in the field of predicting certain cancer patients' prognosis based on the spectrum of mutations.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] For example, up to half of all tumors have a defective p53 gene.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] This mutation is associated with poor prognosis, since those tumor cells are less likely to go into apoptosis or programmed cell death when damaged by therapy.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Telomerase mutations remove additional barriers, extending the number of times a cell can divide.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Other mutations enable the tumor to grow new blood vessels to provide more nutrients, or to metastasize, spreading to other parts of the body.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] However, once a cancer is formed it continues to evolve and to produce sub-clones.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] It was reported in 2012 that a single renal cancer specimen, sampled in nine different areas, had 40 "ubiquitous" mutations, found in all nine areas, 59 mutations shared by some, but not all nine areas, and 29 "private" mutations only present in one area.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] The lineages of cells in which all these DNA alterations accumulate are difficult to trace, but two recent lines of evidence suggest that normal stem cells may be the cells of origin in cancers.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] First, there exists a highly positive correlation (Spearman's rho = 0.81; P < 3.5 × 10−8) between the risk of developing cancer in a tissue and the number of normal stem cell divisions taking place in that same tissue.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] The correlation applied to 31 cancer types and extended across five orders of magnitude.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] This correlation means that if normal stem cells from a tissue divide once, the cancer risk in that tissue is approximately 1X.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] If they divide 1,000 times, the cancer risk is 1,000X.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] And if the normal stem cells from a tissue divide 100,000 times, the cancer risk in that tissue is approximately 100,000X.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] This strongly suggests that the main factor in cancer initiation is the fact that "normal" stem cells divide, which implies that cancer originates in normal, healthy stem cells.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Second, statistics show that most human cancers are diagnosed in older people.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] A possible explanation is that cancers occur because cells accumulate damage through time.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] DNA is the only cellular component that can accumulate damage over the entire course of a life, and stem cells are the only cells that can transmit DNA from the zygote to cells late in life.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Other cells, derived from stem cells, do not keep DNA from the beginning of life until a possible cancer occurs.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] This implies that most cancers arise from normal stem cells.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] The term "field cancerization" was first used in 1953 to describe an area or "field" of epithelium that has been preconditioned by (at that time) largely unknown processes so as to predispose it towards development of cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Since then, the terms "field cancerization" and "field defect" have been used to describe pre-malignant tissue in which new cancers are likely to arise.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Field defects have been identified in association with cancers and are important in progression to cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] However, it was pointed out by Rubin that "the vast majority of studies in cancer research has been done on well-defined tumors in vivo, or on discrete neoplastic foci in vitro.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] It would also be expected that many of the epigenetic alterations present in tumors may have occurred in pre-neoplastic field defects.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] In the colon, a field defect probably arises by natural selection of a mutant or epigenetically altered cell among the stem cells at the base of one of the intestinal crypts on the inside surface of the colon.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] A mutant or epigenetically altered stem cell may replace the other nearby stem cells by natural selection.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] This may cause a patch of abnormal tissue to arise.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] The figure in this section includes a photo of a freshly resected and lengthwise-opened segment of the colon showing a colon cancer and four polyps.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Below the photo there is a schematic diagram of how a large patch of mutant or epigenetically altered cells may have formed, shown by the large area in yellow in the diagram.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] This is indicated in the diagram by four smaller patches of different colors within the large yellow original area.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] In the photo, an apparent field defect in this segment of a colon has generated four polyps (labeled with the size of the polyps, 6mm, 5mm, and two of 3mm, and a cancer about 3 cm across in its longest dimension).
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] These neoplasms are also indicated (in the diagram below the photo) by 4 small tan circles (polyps) and a larger red area (cancer).
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] The cancer in the photo occurred in the cecal area of the colon, where the colon joins the small intestine (labeled) and where the appendix occurs (labeled).
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] The fat in the photo is external to the outer wall of the colon.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] In the segment of colon shown here, the colon was cut open lengthwise to expose its inner surface and to display the cancer and polyps occurring within the inner epithelial lining of the colon.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] The most extensive region of abnormality (the outermost yellow irregular area in the diagram) would reflect the earliest event in formation of a malignant neoplasm.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] In experimental evaluation of specific DNA repair deficiencies in cancers, many specific DNA repair deficiencies were also shown to occur in the field defects surrounding those cancers.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] The table below gives examples for which the DNA repair deficiency in a cancer was shown to be caused by an epigenetic alteration, and the somewhat lower frequencies with which the same epigenetically caused DNA repair deficiency was found in the surrounding field defect.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Some of the small polyps in the field defect shown in the photo of the opened colon segment may be relatively benign neoplasms.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] In a 1996 study of polyps less than 10mm in size found during colonoscopy and followed with repeat colonoscopies for 3 years, 25% remained unchanged in size, 35% regressed or shrank in size and 40% grew in size.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Cancers are known to exhibit genome instability or a "mutator phenotype".
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] The protein-coding DNA within the nucleus is about 1.5% of the total genomic DNA.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Within this protein-coding DNA (called the exome), an average cancer of the breast or colon can have about 60 to 70 protein altering mutations, of which about 3 or 4 may be "driver" mutations, and the remaining ones may be "passenger" mutations.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] However, the average number of DNA sequence mutations in the entire genome (including non-protein-coding regions) within a breast cancer tissue sample is about 20,000.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] In an average melanoma tissue sample (melanomas have a higher exome mutation frequency),) the total number of DNA sequence mutations is about 80,000.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] These high frequencies of mutations in the total nucleotide sequences within cancers suggest that often an early alteration in the field defect giving rise to a cancer (e.g. yellow area in the diagram in the preceding section) is a deficiency in DNA repair.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Large field defects surrounding colon cancers (extending to about 10 cm on each side of a cancer) are found to frequently have epigenetic defects in two or three DNA repair proteins (ERCC1, ERCC4 (XPF) and/or PMS2) in the entire area of the field defect.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] When expression of DNA repair genes is reduced, DNA damage accumulates in cells at a higher than normal rate, and this excess damage causes an increased frequency of mutation and/or epimutation.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Mutation rates strongly increase in cells defective in DNA mismatch repair or in homologous recombinational repair (HRR).
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] A deficiency in DNA repair, itself, can allow DNA damage to accumulate, and error-prone translesion synthesis of some of the damaged areas may give rise to mutations.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] In addition, faulty repair of this accumulated DNA damage may give rise to epimutations.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] These new mutations and/or epimutations may provide a proliferative advantage, generating a field defect.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Although the mutations/epimutations in DNA repair genes do not, themselves, confer a selective advantage, they may be carried along as passengers in cells when the cell acquires an additional mutation/epimutation that does provide a proliferative advantage.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] There are a number of theories of carcinogenesis and cancer treatment that fall outside the mainstream of scientific opinion, due to lack of scientific rationale, logic, or evidence base.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] These theories may be used to justify various alternative cancer treatments.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] They should be distinguished from those theories of carcinogenesis that have a logical basis within mainstream cancer biology, and from which conventionally testable hypotheses can be made.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Several alternative theories of carcinogenesis, however, are based on scientific evidence and are increasingly being acknowledged.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Some researchers believe that cancer may be caused by aneuploidy (numerical and structural abnormalities in chromosomes) rather than by mutations or epimutations.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Cancer has also been considered as a metabolic disease, in which the cellular metabolism of oxygen is diverted from the pathway that generates energy (oxidative phosphorylation) to the pathway that generates reactive oxygen species.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] This causes an energy switch from oxidative phosphorylation to aerobic glycolysis (Warburg effect), and the accumulation of reactive oxygen species leading to oxidative stress ("oxidative stress theory of cancer").
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Another concept of cancer development is based on exposure to weak magnetic and electromagnetic fields and their effects on oxidative stress, known as magnetocarcinogenesis.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] A number of authors have questioned the assumption that cancers result from sequential random mutations as oversimplistic, suggesting instead that cancer results from a failure of the body to inhibit an innate, programmed proliferative tendency.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] A related theory suggests that cancer is an atavism, an evolutionary throwback to an earlier form of multicellular life.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] The genes responsible for uncontrolled cell growth and cooperation between cancer cells are very similar to those that enabled the first multicellular life forms to group together and flourish.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] These genes still exist within the genomes of more complex metazoans, such as humans, although more recently evolved genes keep them in check.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] When the newer controlling genes fail for whatever reason, the cell can revert to its more primitive programming and reproduce out of control.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] The theory is an alternative to the notion that cancers begin with rogue cells that undergo evolution within the body.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Instead, they possess a fixed number of primitive genes that are progressively activated, giving them finite variability.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Cancer thus originates when a rare somatic mutation recombines such fragments into a functional driver of cell proliferation.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Often, the multiple genetic changes that result in cancer may take many years to accumulate.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] During this time, the biological behavior of the pre-malignant cells slowly changes from the properties of normal cells to cancer-like properties.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Pre-malignant tissue can have a distinctive appearance under the microscope.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Among the distinguishing traits of a pre-malignant lesion are an increased number of dividing cells, variation in nuclear size and shape, variation in cell size and shape, loss of specialized cell features, and loss of normal tissue organization.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Dysplasia is an abnormal type of excessive cell proliferation characterized by loss of normal tissue arrangement and cell structure in pre-malignant cells.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] These early neoplastic changes must be distinguished from hyperplasia, a reversible increase in cell division caused by an external stimulus, such as a hormonal imbalance or chronic irritation.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] The most severe cases of dysplasia are referred to as *carcinoma in situ.* In Latin, the term *in situ* means "in place"; *carcinoma in situ* refers to an uncontrolled growth of dysplastic cells that remains in its original location and has not shown invasion into other tissues.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Carcinoma in situ may develop into an invasive malignancy and is usually removed surgically when detected.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Just as a population of animals undergoes evolution, an unchecked population of cells also can undergo "evolution".
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] This undesirable process is called somatic evolution, and is how cancer arises and becomes more malignant over time.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Most changes in cellular metabolism that allow cells to grow in a disorderly fashion lead to cell death.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] However, once cancer begins, cancer cells undergo a process of natural selection: the few cells with new genetic changes that enhance their survival or reproduction multiply faster, and soon come to dominate the growing tumor as cells with less favorable genetic change are out-competed.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] This is the same mechanism by which pathogenic species such as MRSA can become antibiotic-resistant and by which HIV can become drug-resistant, and by which plant diseases and insects can become pesticide-resistant.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] This evolution explains why a cancer relapse often involves cells that have acquired cancer-drug resistance or resistance to radiotherapy.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] These biological changes are classical in carcinomas; other malignant tumors may not need to achieve them all.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] For example, given that tissue invasion and displacement to distant sites are normal properties of leukocytes, these steps are not needed in the development of leukemia.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Nor do the different steps necessarily represent individual mutations.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] For example, inactivation of a single gene, coding for the p53 protein, will cause genomic instability, evasion of apoptosis and increased angiogenesis.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Further, not all the cancer cells are dividing.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Rather, a subset of the cells in a tumor, called cancer stem cells, replicate themselves as they generate differentiated cells.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Normally, once a tissue is injured or infected, damaged cells elicit inflammation by stimulating specific patterns of enzyme activity and cytokine gene expression in surrounding cells.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Discrete clusters ("cytokine clusters") of molecules are secreted, which act as mediators, inducing the activity of subsequent cascades of biochemical changes.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Each cytokine binds to specific receptors on various cell types, and each cell type responds in turn by altering the activity of intracellular signal transduction pathways, depending on the receptors that the cell expresses and the signaling molecules present inside the cell.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Collectively, this reprogramming process induces a stepwise change in cell phenotypes, which will ultimately lead to restoration of tissue function and toward regaining essential structural integrity.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] A tissue can thereby heal, depending on the productive communication between the cells present at the site of damage and the immune system.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] One key factor in healing is the regulation of cytokine gene expression, which enables complementary groups of cells to respond to inflammatory mediators in a manner that gradually produces essential changes in tissue physiology.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Cancer cells have either permanent (genetic) or reversible (epigenetic) changes to their genome, which partly inhibit their communication with surrounding cells and with the immune system.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Cancer cells do not communicate with their tissue microenvironment in a manner that protects tissue integrity; instead, the movement and the survival of cancer cells become possible in locations where they can impair tissue function.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Cancer cells survive by "rewiring" signal pathways that normally protect the tissue from the immune system.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] This alteration of the immune response is evident in early stages of malignancy too.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] One example of tissue function rewiring in cancer is the activity of transcription factor NF-κB.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] NF-κB activates the expression of numerous genes involved in the transition between inflammation and regeneration, which encode cytokines, adhesion factors, and other molecules that can change cell fate.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] This reprogramming of cellular phenotypes normally allows the development of a fully functional intact tissue.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] NF-κB activity is tightly controlled by multiple proteins, which collectively ensure that only discrete clusters of genes are induced by NF-κB in a given cell and at a given time.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] This tight regulation of signal exchange between cells protects the tissue from excessive inflammation, and ensures that different cell types gradually acquire complementary functions and specific positions.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Failure of this mutual regulation between genetic reprogramming and cell interactions allows cancer cells to give rise to metastasis.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Cancer cells respond aberrantly to cytokines, and activate signal cascades that can protect them from the immune system.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p01] Marine elasmobranch fishes such as sharks, stingrays etc. are much less affected by cancer than freshwater fishes, and therefore have stimulated medical research to better understand carcinogenesis.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] In order for cells to start dividing uncontrollably, genes that regulate cell growth must be dysregulated.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Proto-oncogenes are genes that promote cell growth and mitosis, whereas tumor suppressor genes discourage cell growth, or temporarily halt cell division to carry out DNA repair.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Typically, a series of several mutations to these genes is required before a normal cell transforms into a cancer cell.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] This concept is sometimes termed "oncoevolution." Mutations to these genes provide the signals for tumor cells to start dividing uncontrollably.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] But the uncontrolled cell division that characterizes cancer also requires that the dividing cell duplicates all its cellular components to create two daughter cells.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Oncogenes promote cell growth in a variety of ways.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Many can produce hormones, a "chemical messenger" between cells that encourage mitosis, the effect of which depends on the signal transduction of the receiving tissue or cells.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] In other words, when a hormone receptor on a recipient cell is stimulated, the signal is conducted from the surface of the cell to the cell nucleus to affect some change in gene transcription regulation at the nuclear level.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Some oncogenes are part of the signal transduction system itself, or the signal receptors in cells and tissues themselves, thus controlling the sensitivity to such hormones.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Oncogenes often produce mitogens, or are involved in transcription of DNA in protein synthesis, which creates the proteins and enzymes responsible for producing the products and biochemicals cells use and interact with.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Mutations in proto-oncogenes, which are the normally quiescent counterparts of oncogenes, can modify their expression and function, increasing the amount or activity of the product protein.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] When this happens, the proto-oncogenes become oncogenes, and this transition upsets the normal balance of cell cycle regulation in the cell, making uncontrolled growth possible.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] The chance of cancer cannot be reduced by removing proto-oncogenes from the genome, even if this were possible, as they are critical for the growth, repair, and homeostasis of the organism.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] It is only when they become mutated that the signals for growth become excessive.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] One of the first oncogenes to be defined in cancer research is the ras oncogene.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Mutations in the Ras family of proto-oncogenes (comprising H-Ras, N-Ras, and K-Ras) are very common, being found in 20% to 30% of all human tumors.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Ras was originally identified in the Harvey sarcoma virus genome, and researchers were surprised that not only is this gene present in the human genome but also when ligated to a stimulating control element, it could induce cancers in cell line cultures.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] New mechanisms were proposed recently that the cell transformation during carcinogenesis was decided by the overall threshold of the oncogene networks (such as Ras signaling) but not by the status of the individual oncogene.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Proto-oncogenes promote cell growth in a variety of ways.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Many can produce hormones, "chemical messengers" between cells that encourage mitosis, the effect of which depends on the signal transduction of the receiving tissue or cells.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Some are responsible for the signal transduction system and signal receptors in cells and tissues themselves, thus controlling the sensitivity to such hormones.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] They often produce mitogens, or are involved in transcription of DNA in protein synthesis, which create the proteins and enzymes responsible for producing the products and biochemicals cells use and interact with.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Mutations in proto-oncogenes can modify their expression and function, increasing the amount or activity of the product protein.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] When this happens, they become oncogenes, and, thus, cells have a higher chance of dividing excessively and uncontrollably.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] The chance of cancer cannot be reduced by removing proto-oncogenes from the genome, as they are critical for growth, repair and homeostasis of the body.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] A gene possessing a growth-promoting role may increase the carcinogenic potential of a cell, under the condition that all necessary cellular mechanisms that permit growth are activated.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] This condition also includes the inactivation of specific tumor suppressor genes (see below).
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] If the condition is not fulfilled, the cell may cease to grow and can proceed to die.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] This makes identification of the stage and type of cancer cell that grows under the control of a given oncogene crucial for the development of treatment strategies.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Tumor suppressor genes code for anti-proliferation signals and proteins that suppress mitosis and cell growth.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Generally, tumor suppressors are transcription factors that are activated by cellular stress or DNA damage.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Often DNA damage will cause the presence of free-floating genetic material as well as other signs, and will trigger enzymes and pathways that lead to the activation of tumor suppressor genes.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] The functions of such genes is to arrest the progression of the cell cycle in order to carry out DNA repair, preventing mutations from being passed on to daughter cells.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] The p53 protein, one of the most important studied tumor suppressor genes, is a transcription factor activated by many cellular stressors including hypoxia and ultraviolet radiation damage.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Despite nearly half of all cancers possibly involving alterations in p53, its tumor suppressor function is poorly understood. p53 clearly has two functions: one a nuclear role as a transcription factor, and the other a cytoplasmic role in regulating the cell cycle, cell division, and apoptosis.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] The Warburg effect is the preferential use of glycolysis for energy to sustain cancer growth. p53 has been shown to regulate the shift from the respiratory to the glycolytic pathway.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] However, a mutation can damage the tumor suppressor gene itself, or the signal pathway that activates it, "switching it off".
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] The invariable consequence of this is that DNA repair is hindered or inhibited: DNA damage accumulates without repair, inevitably leading to cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Mutations of tumor suppressor genes that occur in germline cells are passed along to offspring, and increase the likelihood for cancer diagnoses in subsequent generations.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Members of these families have increased incidence and decreased latency of multiple tumors.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] The tumor types are typical for each type of tumor suppressor gene mutation, with some mutations causing particular cancers, and other mutations causing others.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] The mode of inheritance of mutant tumor suppressors is that an affected member inherits a defective copy from one parent, and a normal copy from the other.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] For instance, individuals who inherit one mutant *p53* allele (and are therefore heterozygous for mutated *p53*) can develop melanomas and pancreatic cancer, known as Li-Fraumeni syndrome.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Other inherited tumor suppressor gene syndromes include *Rb* mutations, linked to retinoblastoma, and *APC* gene mutations, linked to adenopolyposis colon cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Adenopolyposis colon cancer is associated with thousands of polyps in colon while young, leading to colon cancer at a relatively early age.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Finally, inherited mutations in *BRCA1* and *BRCA2* lead to early onset of breast cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Development of cancer was proposed in 1971 to depend on at least two mutational events.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] In what became known as the Knudson two-hit hypothesis, an inherited, germ-line mutation in a tumor suppressor gene would cause cancer only if another mutation event occurred later in the organism's life, inactivating the other allele of that tumor suppressor gene.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Usually, oncogenes are dominant, as they contain gain-of-function mutations, while mutated tumor suppressors are recessive, as they contain loss-of-function mutations.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Each cell has two copies of the same gene, one from each parent, and under most cases gain of function mutations in just one copy of a particular proto-oncogene is enough to make that gene a true oncogene.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] On the other hand, loss of function mutations need to happen in both copies of a tumor suppressor gene to render that gene completely non-functional.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] However, cases exist in which one mutated copy of a tumor suppressor gene can render the other, wild-type copy non-functional.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] This phenomenon is called the *dominant negative effect* and is observed in many p53 mutations.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Knudson's two hit model has recently been challenged by several investigators.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Inactivation of one allele of some tumor suppressor genes is sufficient to cause tumors.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] This phenomenon is called haploinsufficiency and has been demonstrated by a number of experimental approaches.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Tumors caused by haploinsufficiency usually have a later age of onset when compared with those by a two hit process.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] In general, mutations in both types of genes are required for cancer to occur.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] For example, a mutation limited to one oncogene would be suppressed by normal mitosis control and tumor suppressor genes, first hypothesised by the Knudson hypothesis.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] A mutation to only one tumor suppressor gene would not cause cancer either, due to the presence of many "backup" genes that duplicate its functions.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] It is only when enough proto-oncogenes have mutated into oncogenes, and enough tumor suppressor genes deactivated or damaged, that the signals for cell growth overwhelm the signals to regulate it, that cell growth quickly spirals out of control.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Often, because these genes regulate the processes that prevent most damage to genes themselves, the rate of mutations increases as one gets older, because DNA damage forms a feedback loop.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Mutation of tumor suppressor genes that are passed on to the next generation of not merely cells, but their offspring, can cause increased likelihoods for cancers to be inherited.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Members within these families have increased incidence and decreased latency of multiple tumors.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] The mode of inheritance of mutant tumor suppressors is that affected member inherits a defective copy from one parent, and a normal copy from another.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Because mutations in tumor suppressors act in a recessive manner (note, however, there are exceptions), the loss of the normal copy creates the cancer phenotype.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] For instance, individuals that are heterozygous for p53 mutations are often victims of Li-Fraumeni syndrome, and that are heterozygous for Rb mutations develop retinoblastoma.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] In similar fashion, mutations in the adenomatous polyposis coli gene are linked to adenopolyposis colon cancer, with thousands of polyps in the colon while young, whereas mutations in BRCA1 and BRCA2 lead to early onset of breast cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] A new idea announced in 2011 is an extreme version of multiple mutations, called *chromothripsis* by its proponents.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] This idea, affecting only 2–3% of cases of cancer, although up to 25% of bone cancers, involves the catastrophic shattering of a chromosome into tens or hundreds of pieces and then being patched back together incorrectly.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] This shattering probably takes place when the chromosomes are compacted during normal cell division, but the trigger for the shattering is unknown.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Under this model, cancer arises as the result of a single, isolated event, rather than the slow accumulation of multiple mutations.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Many mutagens are also carcinogens, but some carcinogens are not mutagens.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Examples of carcinogens that are not mutagens include alcohol and estrogen.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] These are thought to promote cancers through their stimulating effect on the rate of cell mitosis.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Faster rates of mitosis increasingly leave fewer opportunities for repair enzymes to repair damaged DNA during DNA replication, increasing the likelihood of a genetic mistake.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] A mistake made during mitosis can lead to the daughter cells' receiving the wrong number of chromosomes, which leads to aneuploidy and may lead to cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Infection by *H. pylori* causes no symptoms in about 80% of those infected.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] About 75% of individuals infected with *H. pylori* develop gastritis.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Thus, the usual consequence of *H. pylori* infection is chronic asymptomatic gastritis.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Because of the usual lack of symptoms, when gastric cancer is finally diagnosed it is often fairly advanced.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] More than half of gastric cancer patients have lymph node metastasis when they are initially diagnosed.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] The gastritis caused by *H. pylori* is accompanied by inflammation, characterized by infiltration of neutrophils and macrophages to the gastric epithelium, which favors the accumulation of pro-inflammatory cytokines and reactive oxygen species/reactive nitrogen species (ROS/RNS).
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] The substantial presence of ROS/RNS causes DNA damage including 8-oxo-2'-deoxyguanosine (8-OHdG).
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] In addition to the oxidative DNA damage 8-OHdG, *H. pylori* infection causes other characteristic DNA damages including DNA double-strand breaks.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] As reviewed by Santos and Ribeiro *H. pylori* infection is associated with epigenetically reduced efficiency of the DNA repair machinery, which favors the accumulation of mutations and genomic instability as well as gastric carcinogenesis.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] In particular, Raza et al. showed that expression of two DNA repair proteins, ERCC1 and PMS2, was severely reduced once *H. pylori* infection had progressed to cause dyspepsia.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Dyspepsia occurs in about 20% of infected individuals.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] In addition, as reviewed by Raza et al., human gastric infection with *H. pylori* causes epigenetically reduced protein expression of DNA repair proteins MLH1, MGMT and MRE11.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Reduced DNA repair in the presence of increased DNA damage increases carcinogenic mutations and is likely a significant cause of *H. pylori* carcinogenesis.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Other bacteria might also play a role in carcinogenesis.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Checkpoint control of the cell cycle and apoptosis by p53 is inhibited by the mycoplasma bacterium, allowing cells with DNA damage to "run an apoptotic red light" and proceed through the cell cycle.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Furthermore, many cancers originate from a viral infection; this is especially true in animals such as birds, but less so in humans.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] 12% of human cancers can be attributed to a viral infection.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] The mode of virally induced tumors can be divided into two, *acutely transforming* or *slowly transforming*.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] In acutely transforming viruses, the viral particles carry a gene that encodes for an overactive oncogene called viral-oncogene (v-onc), and the infected cell is transformed as soon as v-onc is expressed.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] In contrast, in slowly transforming viruses, the virus genome is inserted, especially as viral genome insertion is an obligatory part of retroviruses, near a proto-oncogene in the host genome.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] The viral promoter or other transcription regulation elements, in turn, cause over-expression of that proto-oncogene, which, in turn, induces uncontrolled cellular proliferation.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Because viral genome insertion is not specific to proto-oncogenes and the chance of insertion near that proto-oncogene is low, slowly transforming viruses have very long tumor latency compared to acutely transforming virus, which already carries the viral-oncogene.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Viruses that are known to cause cancer such as HPV (cervical cancer), Hepatitis B (liver cancer), and EBV (a type of lymphoma), are all DNA viruses.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] It is thought that when the virus infects a cell, it inserts a part of its own DNA near the cell growth genes, causing cell division.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] The group of changed cells that are formed from the first cell dividing all have the same viral DNA near the cell growth genes.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] The group of changed cells are now special because one of the normal controls on growth has been lost.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Depending on their location, cells can be damaged through radiation, chemicals from cigarette smoke, and inflammation from bacterial infection or other viruses.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Cells often die if they are damaged, through failure of a vital process or the immune system, however, sometimes damage will knock out a single cancer gene.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] In an old person, there are thousands, tens of thousands, or hundreds of thousands of knocked-out cells.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] The chance that any one would form a cancer is very low.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] When the damage occurs in any area of changed cells, something different occurs.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Each of the cells has the potential for growth.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] The changed cells will divide quicker when the area is damaged by physical, chemical, or viral agents.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] A vicious circle has been set up: Damaging the area will cause the changed cells to divide, causing a greater likelihood that they will experience knock-outs.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] This model of carcinogenesis is popular because it explains why cancers grow.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] It would be expected that cells that are damaged through radiation would die or at least be worse off because they have fewer genes working; viruses increase the number of genes working.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] One thought is that we may end up with thousands of vaccines to prevent every virus that can change our cells.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Viruses can have different effects on different parts of the body.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] It may be possible to prevent a number of different cancers by immunizing against one viral agent.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] It is likely that HPV, for instance, has a role in cancers of the mucous membranes of the mouth.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Certain parasitic worms are known to be carcinogenic.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Epigenetics is the study of the regulation of gene expression through chemical, non-mutational changes in DNA structure.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] The theory of epigenetics in cancer pathogenesis is that non-mutational changes to DNA can lead to alterations in gene expression.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Normally, oncogenes are silent, for example, because of DNA methylation.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Loss of that methylation can induce the aberrant expression of oncogenes, leading to cancer pathogenesis.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Known mechanisms of epigenetic change include DNA methylation, and methylation or acetylation of histone proteins bound to chromosomal DNA at specific locations.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Classes of medications, known as HDAC inhibitors and DNA methyltransferase inhibitors, can re-regulate the epigenetic signaling in the cancer cell.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Epimutations include methylations or demethylations of the CpG islands of the promoter regions of genes, which result in repression or de-repression, respectively of gene expression.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Epimutations can also occur by acetylation, methylation, phosphorylation or other alterations to histones, creating a histone code that represses or activates gene expression, and such histone epimutations can be important epigenetic factors in cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] In addition, carcinogenic epimutation can occur through alterations of chromosome architecture caused by proteins such as HMGA2.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] A further source of epimutation is due to increased or decreased expression of microRNAs (miRNAs).
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] A new way of looking at carcinogenesis comes from integrating the ideas of developmental biology into oncology.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] The cancer stem cell hypothesis proposes that the different kinds of cells in a heterogeneous tumor arise from a single cell, termed Cancer Stem Cell.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Cancer stem cells may arise from transformation of adult stem cells or differentiated cells within a body.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] These cells persist as a subcomponent of the tumor and retain key stem cell properties.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] They give rise to a variety of cells, are capable of self-renewal and homeostatic control.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Furthermore, the relapse of cancer and the emergence of metastasis are also attributed to these cells.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] The cancer stem cell hypothesis does not contradict earlier concepts of carcinogenesis.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] The cancer stem cell hypothesis has been a proposed mechanism that contributes to tumour heterogeneity.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] While genetic and epigenetic alterations in tumor suppressor genes and oncogenes change the behavior of cells, those alterations, in the end, result in cancer through their effects on the population of neoplastic cells and their microenvironment.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Mutant cells in neoplasms compete for space and resources.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Thus, a clone with a mutation in a tumor suppressor gene or oncogene will expand only in a neoplasm if that mutation gives the clone a competitive advantage over the other clones and normal cells in its microenvironment.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Thus, the process of carcinogenesis is formally a process of Darwinian evolution, known as somatic or clonal evolution.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Furthermore, in light of the Darwinistic mechanisms of carcinogenesis, it has been theorized that the various forms of cancer can be categorized as pubertal and gerontological.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] Anthropological research is currently being conducted on cancer as a natural evolutionary process through which natural selection destroys environmentally inferior phenotypes while supporting others.
[src:cancer-biology/carcinogenesis-p02] According to this theory, cancer comes in two separate types: from birth to the end of puberty (approximately age 20) teleologically inclined toward supportive group dynamics, and from mid-life to death (approximately age 40+) teleologically inclined away from overpopulated group dynamics.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Cancer occurs after cells are genetically altered to proliferate rapidly and indefinitely.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] This uncontrolled proliferation by mitosis produces a primary heterogeneic tumour.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] The cells which constitute the tumor eventually undergo metaplasia, followed by dysplasia then anaplasia, resulting in a malignant phenotype.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] This malignancy allows for invasion into the circulation, followed by invasion to a second site for tumorigenesis.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Some cancer cells, known as circulating tumor cells (CTCs), are able to penetrate the walls of lymphatic or blood vessels, and circulate through the bloodstream to other sites and tissues in the body.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] This process, known respectively as *lymphatic* or *hematogenous* spread, allows not only single cells but also groups of cells, or CTC clusters, to travel.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Evidence suggests that CTC clusters may retain their multicellular configuration throughout metastasis, enhancing their ability to establish secondary tumors.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] This perspective aligns with the cancer exodus hypothesis, which posits that maintaining this cluster structure contributes to a higher metastatic potential.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Metastasis is one of the hallmarks of cancer, distinguishing it from benign tumors.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Most cancers can metastasize, although in varying degrees.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Basal cell carcinoma for example rarely metastasizes.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] When tumor cells metastasize, the new tumor is called a *secondary* or *metastatic* tumor, and its cells are similar to those in the original or primary tumor.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] This means that if breast cancer metastasizes to the lungs, the secondary tumor is made up of abnormal breast cells, not of abnormal lung cells.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] The tumor in the lung is then called *metastatic breast cancer*, not *lung cancer*.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Metastasis is a key element in cancer staging systems such as the TNM staging system, where it represents the "M".
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] In overall stage grouping, metastasis places a cancer in Stage IV.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] The possibilities of curative treatment are greatly reduced, or often entirely removed when a cancer has metastasized.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Initially, nearby lymph nodes are struck early.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] The lungs, liver, brain, and bones are the most common metastasis locations from solid tumors.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Although advanced cancer may cause pain, it is often not the first symptom.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Some patients, however, do not show any symptoms.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Metastatic tumors are very common in the late stages of cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] The spread of metastasis may occur via the blood or the lymphatics or through both routes.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] The most common sites of metastases are the lungs, liver, brain, and the bones.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Currently, three main theories have been proposed to explain the metastatic pathway of cancer: the epithelial-mesenchymal transition (EMT) and mesenchymal-epithelial transition (MET) hypothesis, the cancer stem cell hypothesis, and the macrophage–cancer cell fusion hybrid hypothesis.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Some new hypotheses were suggested as well, i.e., under the effect of particular biochemical and/or physical stressors, cancer cells can undergo nuclear expulsion with subsequent macrophage engulfment and fusion, with the formation of cancer fusion cells (CFCs).
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Understanding the enigma of cancer cell spread to distant sites, which accounts for over 90% of cancer-related deaths, necessitates comprehensive investigation.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Key outstanding questions revolve around the survival and migration of cancer cells, such as the nucleus, as they face challenges in passage through capillary valves and hydrodynamic shear forces in the circulation system, making CTCs an unlikely source of metastasis.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Moreover, understanding how cancer cells adapt to the metastatic niche and remain dormant (tumor dormancy) for extended periods presents difficult questions that require further investigation.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] In addition to genetic and biochemical regulation, mechanical forces and the physical properties of cancer cells and their surrounding microenvironment play an important role across multiple stages of metastasis, including invasion, intravasation, circulation, extravasation, and colonisation.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Metastasis involves a complex series of steps in which cancer cells leave the original tumor site and migrate to other parts of the body via the bloodstream, via the lymphatic system, or by direct extension.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] To do so, malignant cells break away from the primary tumor and attach to and degrade proteins that make up the surrounding extracellular matrix (ECM), which separates the tumor from adjoining tissues.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] By degrading these proteins, cancer cells are able to breach the ECM and escape.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] The location of the metastases is not always random, with different types of cancer tending to spread to particular organs and tissues at a rate that is higher than expected by statistical chance alone.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Breast cancer, for example, tends to metastasize to the bones and lungs.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] This specificity seems to be mediated by soluble signal molecules such as chemokines and transforming growth factor beta.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] The body resists metastasis by a variety of mechanisms through the actions of a class of proteins known as metastasis suppressors, of which about a dozen are known.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Human cells exhibit different kinds of motion: collective motility, mesenchymal-type movement, and amoeboid movement.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Cancer cells often opportunistically switch between different kinds of motion.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Some cancer researchers hope to find treatments that can stop or at least slow down the spread of cancer by somehow blocking some necessary step in one or more kinds of motion.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] All steps of the metastatic cascade involve a number of physical processes.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Cell migration requires the generation of forces, and when cancer cells transmigrate through the vasculature, this requires physical gaps in the blood vessels to form.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Besides forces, the regulation of various types of cell-cell and cell-matrix adhesions is crucial during metastasis.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] The metastatic steps are critically regulated by various cell types, including the blood vessel cells (endothelial cells), immune cells or stromal cells.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] The growth of a new network of blood vessels, called tumor angiogenesis, is a crucial hallmark of cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] It has therefore been suggested that angiogenesis inhibitors would prevent the growth of metastases.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Endothelial progenitor cells have been shown to have a strong influence on metastasis and angiogenesis.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Endothelial progenitor cells are important in tumor growth, angiogenesis and metastasis, and can be marked using the Inhibitor of DNA Binding 1 (ID1).
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] This novel finding meant that investigators gained the ability to track endothelial progenitor cells from the bone marrow to the blood to the tumor-stroma and even incorporated in tumor vasculature.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Endothelial progenitor cells incorporated in tumor vasculature suggests that this cell type in blood-vessel development is important in a tumor setting and metastasis.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Furthermore, ablation of the endothelial progenitor cells in the bone marrow can lead to a significant decrease in tumor growth and vasculature development.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Therefore, endothelial progenitor cells are important in tumor biology and present novel therapeutic targets.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] The immune system is typically deregulated in cancer and affects many stages of tumor progression, including metastasis.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Epigenetic regulation also plays an important role in the metastatic outgrowth of disseminated tumor cells.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Metastases display alterations in histone modifications, such as H3K4-methylation and H3K9-methylation, when compared to matching primary tumors.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] These epigenetic modifications in metastases may allow the proliferation and survival of disseminated tumor cells in distant organs.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] A recent study shows that PKC-iota promotes melanoma cell invasion by activating Vimentin during EMT.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] PKC-iota inhibition or knockdown resulted in an increase in E-cadherin and RhoA levels while decreasing total Vimentin, phosphorylated Vimentin (S39) and Par6 in metastatic melanoma cells.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] These results suggested that PKC-ι is involved in signaling pathways which upregulate EMT in melanoma thereby directly stimulates metastasis.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Recently, a series of high-profile experiments suggests that the co-option of intercellular cross-talk mediated by exosome vesicles is a critical factor involved in all steps of the invasion-metastasis cascade.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] The spread of a malignancy into body cavities can occur via penetrating the surface of the peritoneal (called peritoneal carcinomatosis), pleural, pericardial, or subarachnoid spaces.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] For example, ovarian tumors can spread transperitoneally to the surface of the liver.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Lymphatic spread allows the transport of tumor cells to regional lymph nodes near the primary tumor and ultimately, to other parts of the body.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] This is called nodal involvement, positive nodes, or regional disease.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] "Positive nodes" is a term that would be used by medical specialists to describe regional lymph nodes that tested positive for malignancy.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] It is common medical practice to test by biopsy at least one lymph node near a tumor site when carrying out surgery to examine or remove a tumor.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] This lymph node is then called a sentinel lymph node.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Lymphatic spread is the most common route of initial metastasis for carcinomas.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] In contrast, it is uncommon for a sarcoma to metastasize via this route.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Localized spread to regional lymph nodes near the primary tumor is not normally counted as a metastasis, although this is a sign of a worse outcome.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] The lymphatic system does eventually drain from the thoracic duct and right lymphatic duct into the systemic venous system at the venous angle and into the brachiocephalic veins, and therefore these metastatic cells can also eventually spread through the haematogenous route.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] This is typical route of metastasis for sarcomas, but it is also the favored route for certain types of carcinoma, such as renal cell carcinoma originating in the kidney and follicular carcinomas of the thyroid.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Because of their thinner walls, veins are more frequently invaded than are arteries, and metastasis tends to follow the pattern of venous flow.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] That is, hematogenous spread often follows distinct patterns depending on the location of the primary tumor.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] For example, colorectal cancer spreads primarily through the portal vein to the liver.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Some tumors, especially carcinomas may metastasize along anatomical canalicular spaces.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] These spaces include for example the bile ducts, the urinary system, the airways and the subarachnoid space.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] The process is similar to that of transcoelomic spread.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] However, often it remains unclear whether simultaneously diagnosed tumors of a canalicular system are one metastatic process or in fact independent tumors caused by the same agent (field cancerization).
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] There is a propensity for certain tumors to seed in particular organs.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] This was first discussed as the **seed and soil theory** by Stephen Paget in 1889.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] The propensity for a metastatic cell to spread to a particular organ is termed 'organotropism'.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] For example, prostate cancer usually metastasizes to the bones.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] In a similar manner, colon cancer has a tendency to metastasize to the liver.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Stomach cancer often metastasises to the ovary in women, when it is called a Krukenberg tumor.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] According to the seed and soil theory, it is difficult for cancer cells to survive outside their region of origin, so in order to metastasize they must find a location with similar characteristics.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] For example, breast tumor cells, which gather calcium ions from breast milk, metastasize to bone tissue, where they can gather calcium ions from bone.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Melanoma spreads to the brain, presumably because neural tissue and melanocytes arise from the same cell line in the embryo.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] In 1928, James Ewing challenged the seed and soil theory, and proposed that metastasis occurs purely by anatomic and mechanical routes.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] This hypothesis has been recently utilized to suggest several hypotheses about the life cycle of circulating tumor cells (CTCs) and to postulate that the patterns of spread could be better understood through a 'filter and flow' perspective.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] However, contemporary evidences indicate that the primary tumour may dictate organotropic metastases by inducing the formation of pre-metastatic niches at distant sites, where incoming metastatic cells may engraft and colonise.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Specifically, exosome vesicles secreted by tumours have been shown to home to pre-metastatic sites, where they activate pro-metastatic processes such as angiogenesis and modify the immune contexture, so as to foster a favourable microenvironment for secondary tumour growth.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] It is theorized that metastasis always coincides with a primary cancer, and, as such, is a tumor that started from a cancer cell or cells in another part of the body.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] However, over 10% of patients presenting to oncology units will have metastases without a primary tumor found.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] In these cases, doctors refer to the primary tumor as "unknown" or "occult," and the patient is said to have cancer of unknown primary origin (CUP) or unknown primary tumors (UPT).
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] It is estimated that 3% of all cancers are of unknown primary origin.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Studies have shown that, if simple questioning does not reveal the cancer's source (coughing up blood—"probably lung", urinating blood—"probably bladder"), complex imaging will not either.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] In some of these cases a primary tumor may appear later.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] The use of immunohistochemistry has permitted pathologists to give an identity to many of these metastases.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] However, imaging of the indicated area only occasionally reveals a primary.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] In rare cases (e.g., of melanoma), no primary tumor is found, even on autopsy.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] It is therefore thought that some primary tumors can regress completely, but leave their metastases behind.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] In other cases, the tumor might just be too small and/or in an unusual location to be diagnosed.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] The cells in a metastatic tumor resemble those in the primary tumor.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Once the cancerous tissue is examined under a microscope to determine the cell type, a doctor can usually tell whether that type of cell is normally found in the part of the body from which the tissue sample was taken.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] For instance, breast cancer cells look the same whether they are found in the breast or have spread to another part of the body.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] So, if a tissue sample taken from a tumor in the lung contains cells that look like breast cells, the doctor determines that the lung tumor is a secondary tumor.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Still, the determination of the primary tumor can often be very difficult, and the pathologist may have to use several adjuvant techniques, such as immunohistochemistry, FISH (fluorescent in situ hybridization), and others.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Despite the use of techniques, in some cases the primary tumor remains unidentified.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Metastatic cancers may be found at the same time as the primary tumor, or months or years later.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] When a second tumor is found in a patient that has been treated for cancer in the past, it is more often a metastasis than another primary tumor.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] It was previously thought that most cancer cells have a low metastatic potential and that there are rare cells that develop the ability to metastasize through the development of somatic mutations.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] According to this theory, diagnosis of metastatic cancers is only possible after the event of metastasis.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Traditional means of diagnosing cancer (e.g. a biopsy) would only investigate a subpopulation of the cancer cells and would very likely not sample from the subpopulation with metastatic potential.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] The somatic mutation theory of metastasis development has not been substantiated in human cancers.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Rather, it seems that the genetic state of the primary tumor reflects the ability of that cancer to metastasize.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Research comparing gene expression between primary and metastatic adenocarcinomas identified a subset of genes whose expression could distinguish primary tumors from metastatic tumors, dubbed a "metastatic signature." Up-regulated genes in the signature include: SNRPF, HNRPAB, DHPS and securin.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Actin, myosin and MHC class II down-regulation was also associated with the signature.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Additionally, the metastatic-associated expression of these genes was also observed in some primary tumors, indicating that cells with the potential to metastasize could be identified concurrently with diagnosis of the primary tumor.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Recent work identified a form of genetic instability in cancer called chromosome instability (CIN) as a driver of metastasis.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] In aggressive cancer cells, loose DNA fragments from unstable chromosomes spill in the cytosol leading to the chronic activation of innate immune pathways, which are hijacked by cancer cells to spread to distant organs.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Expression of this metastatic signature has been correlated with a poor prognosis and has been shown to be consistent in several types of cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Prognosis was shown to be worse for individuals whose primary tumors expressed the metastatic signature.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Additionally, the expression of these metastatic-associated genes was shown to apply to other cancer types in addition to adenocarcinoma.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Metastases of breast cancer, medulloblastoma and prostate cancer all had similar expression patterns of these metastasis-associated genes.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] The identification of this metastasis-associated signature provides promise for identifying cells with metastatic potential within the primary tumor and hope for improving the prognosis of these metastatic-associated cancers.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Additionally, identifying the genes whose expression is changed in metastasis offers potential targets to inhibit metastasis.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Treatment and survival is determined, to a great extent, by whether or not a cancer remains localized or spreads to other locations in the body.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] If the cancer metastasizes to other tissues or organs it usually dramatically increases a patient's likelihood of death.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Some cancers—such as some forms of leukemia, a cancer of the blood, or malignancies in the brain—can kill without spreading at all.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Once a cancer has metastasized it may still be treated with radiosurgery, chemotherapy, radiation therapy, biological therapy, hormone therapy, surgery, or a combination of these interventions ("multimodal therapy").
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] The choice of treatment depends on many factors, including the type of primary cancer, the size and location of the metastases, the patient's age and general health, and the types of treatments used previously.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] In patients diagnosed with CUP it is often still possible to treat the disease even when the primary tumor cannot be located.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Current treatments are rarely able to cure metastatic cancer though some tumors, such as testicular cancer and thyroid cancer, are usually curable.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Palliative care, care aimed at improving the quality of life of people with major illness, has been recommended as part of management programs for metastasis.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Results from a systematic review of the literature on radiation therapy for brain metastases found that there is little evidence to inform comparative effectiveness and patient-centered outcomes on quality of life, functional status, and cognitive effects.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Although metastasis is widely accepted to be the result of the tumor cells migration, there is a hypothesis saying that some metastases are the result of inflammatory processes by abnormal immune cells.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] The existence of metastatic cancers in the absence of primary tumors also suggests that metastasis is not always caused by malignant cells that leave primary tumors.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] The research done by Sarna's team proved that heavily pigmented melanoma cells have Young's modulus about 4.93, when in non-pigmented ones it was only 0.98.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] In another experiment they found that elasticity of melanoma cells is important for its metastasis and growth: non-pigmented tumors were bigger than pigmented and it was much easier for them to spread.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] They showed that there are both pigmented and non-pigmented cells in melanoma tumors, so that they can both be drug-resistant and metastatic.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] The first physician to report the possibility of local metastasis from a primary cancerous source to nearby tissues was Ibn Sina.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] He described a case of breast cancer and metastatic condition in The Canon of Medicine.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] His hypothesis was based on clinical course of the patient.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] In March 2014 researchers discovered the oldest complete example of a human with metastatic cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] The tumors had developed in a 3,000-year-old skeleton found in 2013 in a tomb in Sudan dating back to 1200 BC.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] The skeleton was analyzed using radiography and a scanning electron microscope.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] These findings were published in the *Public Library of Science* journal.
[src:cancer-biology/metastasis] Metastasis is an Ancient Greek word (μετάστασις) meaning "displacement", from μετά, *meta*, "next", and στάσις, *stasis*, "placement".
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] A **neoplasm** (/ˈniːoʊplæzəm, ˈniːə-/) is a type of abnormal and excessive growth of tissue.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] The process that occurs to form or produce a neoplasm is called **neoplasia**.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] The growth of a neoplasm is uncoordinated with that of the normal surrounding tissue, and persists in growing abnormally, even if the original trigger is removed.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] This abnormal growth usually forms a mass, which may be called a **tumour** or **tumor**.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] ICD-10 classifies neoplasms into four main groups: benign neoplasms, in situ neoplasms, malignant neoplasms, and neoplasms of uncertain or unknown behavior.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] Malignant neoplasms are also simply known as cancers and are the focus of oncology.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] Prior to the abnormal growth of tissue, such as neoplasia, cells often undergo an abnormal pattern of growth, such as metaplasia or dysplasia.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] However, metaplasia or dysplasia does not always progress to neoplasia and can occur in other conditions as well.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] The word neoplasm is from Ancient Greek νέος- *neo* 'new' and πλάσμα *plasma* 'formation, creation'.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] A neoplasm can be benign, potentially malignant, or malignant (cancer).
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] Neoplastic tumors are often heterogeneous and contain more than one type of cell, but their initiation and continued growth are usually dependent on a single population of neoplastic cells.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] These cells are presumed to be monoclonal – that is, they are derived from the same cell, and all carry the same genetic or epigenetic anomaly – evident of clonality.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] For lymphoid neoplasms, e.g. lymphoma and leukemia, clonality is proven by the amplification of a single rearrangement of their immunoglobulin gene (for B cell lesions) or T cell receptor gene (for T cell lesions).
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] The demonstration of clonality is now considered to be necessary to identify a lymphoid cell proliferation as neoplastic.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] The word *tumor* or *tumour* comes from the Latin word for *swelling*, which is one of the cardinal signs of inflammation.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] The word originally referred to any form of swelling, neoplastic or not.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] In modern English, *tumor (non-US spelling: tumour)* is used as a synonym for a neoplasm (a solid or fluid-filled cystic lesion that may or may not be formed by an abnormal growth of neoplastic cells) that appears enlarged in size.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] Some neoplasms do not form a tumor; these include leukemia and most forms of carcinoma in situ.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] *Tumor* is also not synonymous with *cancer.* While cancer is by definition malignant, a tumor can be benign, precancerous, or malignant.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] The terms *mass* and *nodule* are often used synonymously with *tumor*.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] Generally speaking, however, the term *tumor* is used generically, without reference to the physical size of the lesion.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] More specifically, the term *mass* is often used when the lesion has a maximal diameter of at least 20 millimeters (mm) in the greatest direction, while the term *nodule* is usually used when the size of the lesion is less than 20 mm in its greatest dimension (25.4 mm = 1 inch).
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] Tumors in humans occur as a result of accumulated genetic and epigenetic alterations within single cells, which cause the cell to divide and expand uncontrollably.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] A neoplasm can be caused by an abnormal proliferation of tissues, which can be caused by genetic mutations.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] Not all types of neoplasms cause a tumorous overgrowth of tissue (such as leukemia or carcinoma in situ); however, similarities between neoplasmic growths and regenerative processes, e.g., dedifferentiation and rapid cell proliferation, have been pointed out.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] Tumor growth has been studied using mathematics and continuum mechanics.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] Vascular tumors such as hemangiomas and lymphangiomas (formed from blood or lymph vessels) are thus looked at as being amalgams of a solid skeleton formed by sticky cells and an organic liquid filling the spaces in which cells can grow.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] Under this type of model, mechanical stresses and strains can be dealt with and their influence on the growth of the tumor and the surrounding tissue and vasculature elucidated.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] Recent findings from experiments that use this model show that active growth of the tumor is restricted to the outer edges of the tumor and that stiffening of the underlying normal tissue inhibits tumor growth as well.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] Benign conditions that are *not* associated with an abnormal proliferation of tissue (such as sebaceous cysts) can also present as tumors, however, but have no malignant potential.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] Examples include breast cysts, which commonly occur during pregnancy and at other times, as well as other encapsulated glandular swellings (thyroid, adrenal gland, pancreas).
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] Encapsulated hematomas, encapsulated necrotic tissue (from an insect bite, foreign body, or other noxious mechanism), keloids (discrete overgrowths of scar tissue) and granulomas may also present as tumors.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] Discrete localized enlargements of normal structures (ureters, blood vessels, intrahepatic or extrahepatic biliary ducts, pulmonary inclusions, or gastrointestinal duplications) due to outflow obstructions or narrowings, or abnormal connections, may also present as a tumor.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] Examples are arteriovenous fistulae or aneurysms (with or without thrombosis), biliary fistulae or aneurysms, sclerosing cholangitis, cysticercosis or hydatid cysts, intestinal duplications, and pulmonary inclusions as seen with cystic fibrosis.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] It can be dangerous to biopsy a number of types of tumor in which the leakage of their contents would potentially be catastrophic.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] When such types of tumors are encountered, diagnostic modalities such as ultrasound, CT scans, MRI, angiograms, and nuclear medicine scans are employed prior to (or during) biopsy or surgical exploration/excision in an attempt to avoid such severe complications.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] DNA damage is considered to be the primary underlying cause of malignant neoplasms known as cancers.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] Its central role in progression to cancer is illustrated in the figure in this section, in the box near the top.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] (The central features of DNA damage, epigenetic alterations and deficient DNA repair in progression to cancer are shown in red.) DNA damage is very common.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] Naturally occurring DNA damages (mostly due to cellular metabolism and the properties of DNA in water at body temperatures) occur at a rate of more than 10,000 new damages, on average, per human cell, per day.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] Additional DNA damages can arise from exposure to exogenous agents.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] Tobacco smoke causes increased exogenous DNA damage, and these DNA damages are the likely cause of lung cancer due to smoking.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] UV light from solar radiation causes DNA damage that is important in melanoma.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] *Helicobacter pylori* infection produces high levels of reactive oxygen species that damage DNA and contributes to gastric cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] Bile acids, at high levels in the colons of humans eating a high-fat diet, also cause DNA damage and contribute to colon cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] Katsurano et al. indicated that macrophages and neutrophils in an inflamed colonic epithelium are the source of reactive oxygen species causing the DNA damages that initiate colonic tumorigenesis (creation of tumors in the colon).
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] Some sources of DNA damage are indicated in the boxes at the top of the figure in this section.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] Individuals with a germline mutation causing deficiency in any of 34 DNA repair genes (see article DNA repair-deficiency disorder) are at increased risk of cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] Some germline mutations in DNA repair genes cause up to 100% lifetime chance of cancer (e.g., p53 mutations).
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] These germline mutations are indicated in a box at the left of the figure with an arrow indicating their contribution to DNA repair deficiency.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] About 70% of malignant (cancerous) neoplasms have no hereditary component and are called "sporadic cancers".
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] Only a minority of sporadic cancers have a deficiency in DNA repair due to mutation in a DNA repair gene.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] However, a majority of sporadic cancers have deficiency in DNA repair due to epigenetic alterations that reduce or silence DNA repair gene expression.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] For example, of 113 sequential colorectal cancers, only four had a missense mutation in the DNA repair gene MGMT, while the majority had reduced MGMT expression due to methylation of the MGMT promoter region (an epigenetic alteration).
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] Five reports present evidence that between 40% and 90% of colorectal cancers have reduced MGMT expression due to methylation of the MGMT promoter region.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] In the other 10 cases, loss of PMS2 expression was likely due to epigenetic overexpression of the microRNA, miR-155, which down-regulates MLH1.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] In further examples, epigenetic defects were found at frequencies of between 13%-100% for the DNA repair genes BRCA1, WRN, FANCB, FANCF, MGMT, MLH1, MSH2, MSH4, ERCC1, XPF, NEIL1 and ATM.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] These epigenetic defects occurred in various cancers, including breast, ovarian, colorectal, and head and neck cancers.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] Two or three deficiencies in expression of ERCC1, XPF or PMS2 occur simultaneously in the majority of the 49 colon cancers evaluated by Facista et al.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] Epigenetic alterations causing reduced expression of DNA repair genes is shown in a central box at the third level from the top of the figure in this section, and the consequent DNA repair deficiency is shown at the fourth level.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] When expression of DNA repair genes is reduced, DNA damages accumulate in cells at a higher than normal level, and these excess damages cause increased frequencies of mutation or epimutation.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] During repair of DNA double strand breaks, or repair of other DNA damages, incompletely cleared sites of repair can cause epigenetic gene silencing.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] DNA repair deficiencies (level 4 in the figure) cause increased DNA damages (level 5 in the figure) which result in increased somatic mutations and epigenetic alterations (level 6 in the figure).
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] Field defects, normal-appearing tissue with multiple alterations (and discussed in the section below), are common precursors to development of the disordered and improperly proliferating clone of tissue in a malignant neoplasm.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] Such field defects (second level from bottom of figure) may have multiple mutations and epigenetic alterations.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] Once a cancer is formed, it usually has genome instability.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] This instability is likely due to reduced DNA repair or excessive DNA damage.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] Because of such instability, the cancer continues to evolve and to produce sub clones.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] For example, a renal cancer, sampled in 9 areas, had 40 ubiquitous mutations, demonstrating tumor heterogeneity (i.e. present in all areas of the cancer), 59 mutations shared by some (but not all areas), and 29 "private" mutations only present in one of the areas of the cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] Various other terms have been used to describe this phenomenon, including *field effect*, *field cancerization*, and *field carcinogenesis*.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] The term *field cancerization* was first used in 1953 to describe an area or "field" of epithelium that has been preconditioned by (at that time) largely unknown processes so as to predispose it towards development of cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] Since then, the terms *field cancerization* and *field defect* have been used to describe pre-malignant tissue in which new cancers are likely to arise.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] Field defects are important in progression to cancer.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] However, in most cancer research, as pointed out by Rubin "The vast majority of studies in cancer research has been done on well-defined tumors in vivo, or on discrete neoplastic foci in vitro.
[src:cancer-biology/neoplasm] Yet there is evidence that more than 80% of the somatic mutations found in mutator phenotype human colorectal tumors occur before the onset of terminal clonal expansion.
